1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:15,615
We're here today
with two wonderful actors,

2
00:00:15,682 --> 00:00:17,951
Go Soo and Lee Jong-hyuk.

3
00:00:18,018 --> 00:00:19,853
Now, Jong-hyuk.

4
00:00:19,919 --> 00:00:22,222
I heard there was someone here
you really wanted to meet.

5
00:00:22,288 --> 00:00:23,356
-Me?
-It's probably not me.

6
00:00:23,423 --> 00:00:24,824
No, it's not you, Sung-ju.

7
00:00:24,891 --> 00:00:26,860
Of course. Who did you want to meet?

8
00:00:26,926 --> 00:00:28,261
-It's Jung-hwan.
-Jung-hwan?

9
00:00:28,328 --> 00:00:29,729
-Yes.
-Why him?

10
00:00:29,796 --> 00:00:32,866
I was a guest for the second season
of <i>Dad! Where Are We Going?</i>

11
00:00:32,932 --> 00:00:34,467
-and appeared on the show.
-I see.

12
00:00:34,534 --> 00:00:36,436
-You were a regular in season one.
-Yes.

13
00:00:36,503 --> 00:00:39,873
-Then you were invited back as a guest.
-That's right.

14
00:00:39,939 --> 00:00:43,843
-And we had a drink together once after.
-We grabbed a drink.

15
00:00:44,544 --> 00:00:46,046
It was so nice.

16
00:00:46,112 --> 00:00:47,781
He's so warm-hearted.

17
00:00:47,847 --> 00:00:49,582
You're quite close to Sung-ju, aren't you?

18
00:00:49,649 --> 00:00:52,952
We were really close
back when we did the show with our kids.

19
00:00:53,019 --> 00:00:55,655
-He's a great show host.
-No doubt.

20
00:00:55,722 --> 00:00:57,257
LOOKING FORWARD TO A COMPLIMENT

21
00:00:57,323 --> 00:01:00,226
He's like a jukebox
that plays music when you insert a coin.

22
00:01:00,293 --> 00:01:02,128
He only does his pay's worth,

23
00:01:02,195 --> 00:01:03,296
then he goes home.

24
00:01:03,363 --> 00:01:04,464
DISSED BY A CLOSE FRIEND

25
00:01:04,531 --> 00:01:05,732
-Like a jukebox.
-That guy.

26
00:01:05,799 --> 00:01:06,766
MC Jukebox.

27
00:01:06,833 --> 00:01:08,968
-That guy!
-The jukebox of show hosts.

28
00:01:09,035 --> 00:01:10,537
MISCHIEVOUS JONG-HYUK

29
00:01:10,603 --> 00:01:12,138
During <i>Dad! Where Are We Going?</i>,

30
00:01:12,205 --> 00:01:13,840
I found him the most uncomfortable.

31
00:01:13,907 --> 00:01:15,775
-What? Why?
-Yes.

32
00:01:15,842 --> 00:01:18,044
-You're bringing it up now?
-Talk it out. It's in the past.

33
00:01:18,111 --> 00:01:20,246
-He's not acting nice right now.
-He's not.

34
00:01:20,313 --> 00:01:21,915
-What made you feel that way?
-In the show,

35
00:01:21,981 --> 00:01:24,150
-we should do our part as dads, right?
-Yes.

36
00:01:24,217 --> 00:01:26,319
But he never did what a dad should do.

37
00:01:26,386 --> 00:01:27,420
NODS

38
00:01:27,487 --> 00:01:28,621
He let the kids go freely.

39
00:01:28,688 --> 00:01:29,556
FREE-RANGE PARENTING

40
00:01:29,622 --> 00:01:33,126
He'd just roam around freely,
wondering if there's anything to snack on.

41
00:01:33,193 --> 00:01:34,527
I'd ask, "What's Daddy doing?"

42
00:01:34,594 --> 00:01:35,829
And he'd go, "He's sleeping."

43
00:01:36,529 --> 00:01:38,598
He never tried hard,
but he was so popular.

44
00:01:38,665 --> 00:01:40,066
As you can see, he gets jealous.

45
00:01:40,133 --> 00:01:41,434
-So jealous.
-He gets jealous.

46
00:01:41,501 --> 00:01:45,205
I often thought to myself,
"Lee Jong-hyuk, that guy…"

47
00:01:45,271 --> 00:01:47,874
One day,
I wanted to get my revenge on him.

48
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:51,044
I have one update about him
to relay to everyone.

49
00:01:51,111 --> 00:01:52,545
His second son,

50
00:01:52,612 --> 00:01:56,349
Joon-su, has enrolled into university
as a Theater and Film major.

51
00:01:56,416 --> 00:01:59,919
His eldest son
was already studying Theater and Film,

52
00:01:59,986 --> 00:02:01,554
and now, so is his second son.

53
00:02:01,621 --> 00:02:04,991
-A family of actors.
-Their dad also studied Theater and Film.

54
00:02:05,058 --> 00:02:06,292
The dad, Tak-soo, and Joon-su.

55
00:02:06,359 --> 00:02:09,529
The father and his sons
are all Theater and Film majors.

56
00:02:09,596 --> 00:02:10,430
JOON-SU: CHUNG-ANG UNIV.

57
00:02:10,497 --> 00:02:11,931
DAD: SEOUL INST. OF ARTS,
TAK-SOO: DONGGUK UNIV.

58
00:02:11,998 --> 00:02:14,334
By any chance, what if your sons go,

59
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:17,971
"Dad, you could've done a better job
when you acted in this piece"?

60
00:02:18,037 --> 00:02:20,373
Joon-su would say things like,

61
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:22,842
"Dad, I think
anyone can perform like you."

62
00:02:23,409 --> 00:02:25,645
JOON-SU'S HARSH CRITICISM

63
00:02:25,712 --> 00:02:27,647
He's always been like that.

64
00:02:27,714 --> 00:02:29,716
One day, Tak-soo came to visit me
at one of my shoots.

65
00:02:29,782 --> 00:02:32,385
He sat by the director,
watched the monitor with him, and said,

66
00:02:32,452 --> 00:02:34,020
"Dad's pronunciation is a bit off."

67
00:02:34,087 --> 00:02:35,522
So I said, "The director
said it was okay."

68
00:02:35,588 --> 00:02:36,956
He said, "Okay?"

69
00:02:37,023 --> 00:02:37,924
"Isn't that a blooper?"

70
00:02:37,991 --> 00:02:39,425
THE ELDEST SON DOUBTS HIS DAD

71
00:02:39,492 --> 00:02:41,027
-Even when the director said it was good?
-Yes.

72
00:02:41,094 --> 00:02:42,729
I said, "The director said
it was okay, kiddo."

73
00:02:45,031 --> 00:02:46,533
"Be quiet."

74
00:02:47,634 --> 00:02:49,602
Now I have another pair of eyes on me.

75
00:02:49,669 --> 00:02:53,006
Some fathers are against their children
taking up the same profession

76
00:02:53,072 --> 00:02:55,041
-as he had.
-That's true.

77
00:02:55,108 --> 00:02:57,644
I didn't oppose them.
They wanted to do it,

78
00:02:57,710 --> 00:03:00,647
so I said, "Go ahead and try,"
which led them to an arts high school.

79
00:03:00,713 --> 00:03:03,149
It's a choice they made for their lives.

80
00:03:03,216 --> 00:03:04,217
HE RESPECTED THEIR DECISION

81
00:03:04,284 --> 00:03:06,653
-Soo, you also have three children.
-Yes.

82
00:03:06,719 --> 00:03:08,955
Do any of them want to start acting?

83
00:03:09,522 --> 00:03:13,893
They don't seem to be interested
in their future endeavors.

84
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:15,828
-They're busy playing.
-What if they want to?

85
00:03:15,895 --> 00:03:18,398
-What if your kid wants to do it?
-If they want to, sure.

86
00:03:18,464 --> 00:03:19,599
-Will you support them?
-Yes.

87
00:03:19,666 --> 00:03:21,834
Chefs, what if your children

88
00:03:21,901 --> 00:03:23,536
want to become chefs like you?

89
00:03:23,603 --> 00:03:25,038
SHAKING HEAD

90
00:03:25,104 --> 00:03:26,873
Nam-no shakes his head. So no?

91
00:03:26,940 --> 00:03:27,874
Never.

92
00:03:27,941 --> 00:03:29,409
-Why not?
-No?

93
00:03:29,475 --> 00:03:31,578
You always have to work on the weekends.

94
00:03:31,644 --> 00:03:34,480
It'd be better
if they had an ordinary office job.

95
00:03:34,547 --> 00:03:36,316
Rest when everyone rests,
eat when everyone eats.

96
00:03:36,382 --> 00:03:37,850
Here's the thing with chefs.

97
00:03:37,917 --> 00:03:42,155
My father would always say his legs hurt
and ask me to massage them.

98
00:03:43,556 --> 00:03:45,491
And now that I've aged,
I can understand him.

99
00:03:45,558 --> 00:03:47,193
I have to stay standing all day.

100
00:03:47,260 --> 00:03:48,461
-Well, you get to stand.
-Yes.

101
00:03:48,528 --> 00:03:49,729
I ran around all day.

102
00:03:51,431 --> 00:03:53,233
What's better? Standing or running?

103
00:03:53,299 --> 00:03:54,567
You stand indoors, right?

104
00:03:54,634 --> 00:03:56,769
It didn't matter if it snowed, rained,

105
00:03:56,836 --> 00:03:58,805
-or the ground froze.
-You're right.

106
00:03:58,871 --> 00:04:00,440
We would rather run.

107
00:04:00,506 --> 00:04:04,277
We have to stand in a room
with high heat and poor ventilation.

108
00:04:04,344 --> 00:04:06,179
Do you know how hot the sun is?

109
00:04:06,246 --> 00:04:07,380
HAS NO COMEBACK

110
00:04:07,447 --> 00:04:09,349
-You don't, right?
-No.

111
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:11,818
You don't know what it feels like
to run at 35 or 38°C.

112
00:04:11,884 --> 00:04:12,885
Gosh.

113
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:16,422
Jong-hyuk is such a great dad.

114
00:04:16,489 --> 00:04:18,091
Instead of promoting his play,

115
00:04:18,157 --> 00:04:21,261
he said he wanted to promote
his son's play.

116
00:04:21,995 --> 00:04:24,564
Tak-soo had an audition

117
00:04:24,631 --> 00:04:26,633
-and got cast.
-He got it?

118
00:04:26,699 --> 00:04:29,168
So he had to take time off from school.

119
00:04:29,235 --> 00:04:31,337
-It felt great.
-I'm sure.

120
00:04:31,404 --> 00:04:34,974
It's a play based on the film,
<i>Dead Poets Society.</i>

121
00:04:35,041 --> 00:04:39,078
He's making his debut on the stage
as one of the students.

122
00:04:39,145 --> 00:04:41,681
Last time I heard,
he had taken up a part-time job.

123
00:04:41,748 --> 00:04:44,817
He's taking time off school
and has nothing to do,

124
00:04:44,884 --> 00:04:47,954
because practice hasn't begun yet.

125
00:04:48,021 --> 00:04:50,323
In the day, he works part-time
at a coffee shop,

126
00:04:50,390 --> 00:04:51,891
and at night, a restaurant.

127
00:04:53,026 --> 00:04:55,128
-He works hard.
-He's free, so he's making money.

128
00:04:55,194 --> 00:04:56,763
-He should.
-And get experience.

129
00:04:57,530 --> 00:04:59,265
He should make money.
Otherwise what? Hang around?

130
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:00,466
A REALIST DAD

131
00:05:00,533 --> 00:05:01,567
You don't give him an allowance?

132
00:05:01,634 --> 00:05:03,136
I pay his transportation stipend.

133
00:05:03,202 --> 00:05:05,338
GIVING HIS SON TRANSPORTATION STIPEND?

134
00:05:05,405 --> 00:05:06,806
He's not doing an event for you.

135
00:05:06,873 --> 00:05:09,208
No, I meant transportation expenses.

136
00:05:09,275 --> 00:05:10,343
Why did I call it a stipend?

137
00:05:10,410 --> 00:05:12,345
EVEN HE HAS NO IDEA

138
00:05:12,412 --> 00:05:16,616
-Do you drink with your sons?
-What's this about seven bottles of soju?

139
00:05:16,683 --> 00:05:19,552
When Tak-soo just became
a college student,

140
00:05:19,619 --> 00:05:22,588
he wanted to drink with me
after a few drinks with his friends.

141
00:05:22,655 --> 00:05:23,956
OH-HO

142
00:05:24,524 --> 00:05:25,758
He said, "So, soju?"

143
00:05:25,825 --> 00:05:28,027
I said, "Sure, the green cap."
He answered, "Oh, come on."

144
00:05:28,094 --> 00:05:31,297
-"Let's have the red cap. Higher proof."
-The red cap?

145
00:05:31,364 --> 00:05:32,799
So he brought some home,

146
00:05:32,865 --> 00:05:35,168
and we began to mix it with other drinks,
which ended up

147
00:05:35,234 --> 00:05:36,669
around seven to eight bottles.

148
00:05:37,437 --> 00:05:40,306
When we were done,
he passed out and fell asleep,

149
00:05:40,373 --> 00:05:41,974
but I got thirsty so I had some beer.

150
00:05:42,041 --> 00:05:44,744
Then, he woke up from his sleep,
saw me, and admitted defeat.

151
00:05:44,811 --> 00:05:45,812
HE SURRENDERED

152
00:05:45,878 --> 00:05:47,814
-He said, "I'm sorry."
-I see.

153
00:05:47,880 --> 00:05:49,782
These days, it's Joon-su.

154
00:05:49,849 --> 00:05:51,017
Joon-su?

155
00:05:51,084 --> 00:05:53,553
After he started university,

156
00:05:53,619 --> 00:05:54,620
I'd ask what he's up to.

157
00:05:54,687 --> 00:05:55,988
He goes, "I'm drinking."

158
00:05:56,055 --> 00:05:57,357
BABY JOON-SU IS NOW 20

159
00:05:57,423 --> 00:06:00,259
He said it so confidently,
so I was more flustered.

160
00:06:00,326 --> 00:06:01,627
When he drinks with his friends,

161
00:06:01,694 --> 00:06:03,429
he starts off with a bottle down
before his friends come.

162
00:06:03,496 --> 00:06:04,497
That's insane.

163
00:06:04,564 --> 00:06:07,367
I said, "The three of us should have a
match and see who can hold his alcohol."

164
00:06:07,934 --> 00:06:09,869
STREET DRUNK FIGHTERS

165
00:06:09,936 --> 00:06:11,404
HEHE

166
00:06:11,471 --> 00:06:14,741
Sung-ju, do you drink with Min-gook?

167
00:06:14,807 --> 00:06:17,810
-I can't hold my alcohol.
-Right. You aren't a drinker.

168
00:06:17,877 --> 00:06:18,745
What about Min-gook?

169
00:06:18,811 --> 00:06:21,814
I think he drinks from time to time
without telling me.

170
00:06:21,881 --> 00:06:23,349
What's wrong with that? He's a grown man.

171
00:06:23,416 --> 00:06:26,285
I don't like to see him
in unkempt condition.

172
00:06:26,352 --> 00:06:29,088
"Kim Min-gook.
Have you been drinking too much?"

173
00:06:29,155 --> 00:06:30,656
How did you know?

174
00:06:32,091 --> 00:06:33,626
You know me too well.

175
00:06:33,693 --> 00:06:35,328
You even know the tone.

176
00:06:35,395 --> 00:06:36,496
"Kim Min-gook."

177
00:06:37,363 --> 00:06:38,998
Jong-hyuk is a huge baseball fan.

178
00:06:39,065 --> 00:06:40,299
ONE OF THE FAMOUS CELEBRITY FANS

179
00:06:40,366 --> 00:06:42,034
Here's how much he loves baseball.

180
00:06:42,101 --> 00:06:45,671
-He holds a record for the first pitch.
-Really?

181
00:06:45,738 --> 00:06:47,874
Among Twins fans,

182
00:06:47,940 --> 00:06:50,276
<i>he's the celebrity who has thrown</i>
<i>the most ceremonial first pitches.</i>

183
00:06:50,343 --> 00:06:52,311
<i>He's done ceremonial first batting too.</i>

184
00:06:52,378 --> 00:06:54,847
-I'm sure all Twins fans know who you are.
-Of course.

185
00:06:54,914 --> 00:06:57,884
While I was shooting a drama called
<i>A Gentleman's Dignity</i>,

186
00:06:57,950 --> 00:06:59,185
I was scheduled to pitch,

187
00:06:59,252 --> 00:07:01,254
-and I was so excited.
-I see.

188
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:02,889
But the director asked,

189
00:07:02,955 --> 00:07:05,558
"Jong-hyuk, do you have to go?"

190
00:07:05,625 --> 00:07:07,126
-To the first pitch?
-Yes.

191
00:07:07,193 --> 00:07:09,328
I said, "It was scheduled a month ago,
so I must go."

192
00:07:10,596 --> 00:07:11,597
So I went.

193
00:07:12,732 --> 00:07:13,800
Then it began to rain.

194
00:07:13,866 --> 00:07:15,802
OH, NO

195
00:07:16,969 --> 00:07:18,171
You were in a tough spot.

196
00:07:18,237 --> 00:07:19,305
ABOUT TO GO CRAZY

197
00:07:19,372 --> 00:07:20,306
You had to wait, right?

198
00:07:20,373 --> 00:07:23,209
-Yes, you have to wait 30 minutes.
-For the rain to stop.

199
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:24,844
If it continues to rain too much…

200
00:07:24,911 --> 00:07:26,312
-Canceled.
-…then it's canceled.

201
00:07:26,379 --> 00:07:27,613
-And then…
-Did you get to do it?

202
00:07:28,147 --> 00:07:31,117
-…the game got rained out.
-It was canceled?

203
00:07:31,184 --> 00:07:32,618
When that happens,

204
00:07:32,685 --> 00:07:34,187
-the players do a ceremony.
-They do.

205
00:07:34,253 --> 00:07:35,755
They do a lap, and then slide.

206
00:07:35,822 --> 00:07:37,223
And then, the PR staff member said,

207
00:07:37,857 --> 00:07:39,559
"Do you want to give it a go?"

208
00:07:40,993 --> 00:07:42,028
"Me?"

209
00:07:42,762 --> 00:07:45,198
-He was just there to pitch.
-No one has ever done that before.

210
00:07:45,865 --> 00:07:46,933
-So did you?
-"I'll do it."

211
00:07:48,668 --> 00:07:50,503
The game was between the Twins and Bears.

212
00:07:50,570 --> 00:07:51,838
AGREED TO DO THE RAINOUT CEREMONY

213
00:07:51,904 --> 00:07:54,874
<i>I think it's the first time</i>
<i>for a ceremonial pitcher or batter</i>

214
00:07:54,941 --> 00:07:58,845
<i>-to do the rainout ceremony.</i>
<i>-You're right.</i>

215
00:07:58,911 --> 00:08:00,346
CLANG

216
00:08:04,217 --> 00:08:05,751
A NICE SLIDE

217
00:08:05,818 --> 00:08:08,855
<i>Lee Jong-hyuk, who was scheduled</i>
<i>to throw the first pitch,</i>

218
00:08:08,921 --> 00:08:11,157
<i>joined the rainout ceremony instead.</i>

219
00:08:11,224 --> 00:08:12,959
-You're a serious fan.
-I am.

220
00:08:13,025 --> 00:08:14,861
When they invite the first pitchers,

221
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:17,029
-they also consider how lucky he is.
-Of course.

222
00:08:17,096 --> 00:08:20,500
Recently, well, last year,
I was caught on the screen in the stands,

223
00:08:20,566 --> 00:08:22,401
and we always lose
whenever I'm caught on TV.

224
00:08:22,969 --> 00:08:23,870
THE LOSING FAIRY?

225
00:08:23,936 --> 00:08:25,404
Does that happen often?

226
00:08:25,471 --> 00:08:27,507
-It's so annoying.
-It's a jinx.

227
00:08:27,573 --> 00:08:30,109
"We always lose
whenever that bleep is here."

228
00:08:30,176 --> 00:08:33,779
"Please stop coming, you bleep, bleep."
I've seen these comments.

229
00:08:34,347 --> 00:08:35,715
HOW HARSH…

230
00:08:35,781 --> 00:08:36,916
-I replied.
-And said what?

231
00:08:36,983 --> 00:08:38,417
"Mind your own."

232
00:08:38,985 --> 00:08:41,020
A TIMID REVENGE

233
00:08:41,087 --> 00:08:43,556
After posting that,
it felt like I sounded stupid.

234
00:08:43,623 --> 00:08:45,691
I added, "You're dead meat
if I see you at the ballpark."

235
00:08:46,359 --> 00:08:47,593
A BRUTAL RESPONSE

236
00:08:47,660 --> 00:08:49,061
"Follow me to the rooftop."

237
00:08:49,128 --> 00:08:50,796
I feel falsely blamed.

238
00:08:50,863 --> 00:08:52,798
A few days ago, one of our chefs went

239
00:08:52,865 --> 00:08:54,433
and threw the first pitch
for the season's first game.

240
00:08:54,500 --> 00:08:56,969
-What?
-One of them pitched for the opening game!

241
00:08:57,036 --> 00:08:58,538
-What?
-That chef was invited!

242
00:08:58,604 --> 00:09:00,273
That's not an easy gig to get.

243
00:09:00,339 --> 00:09:02,408
-Is it Son Jong-won?
-It was me.

244
00:09:02,475 --> 00:09:03,943
THE FIRST PITCHER, JONG-WON

245
00:09:04,010 --> 00:09:06,913
-I'm jealous.
-Pitching for the first game is special.

246
00:09:06,979 --> 00:09:07,813
I'm jealous.

247
00:09:07,880 --> 00:09:09,849
The opening game sets the energy…

248
00:09:09,916 --> 00:09:12,018
-It's the beginning.
-…for the rest of the year.

249
00:09:12,084 --> 00:09:12,919
-Did they win?
-Did they win?

250
00:09:12,985 --> 00:09:15,388
Yes, thankfully,
they won two games in a row.

251
00:09:15,454 --> 00:09:16,589
WON 2 GAMES IN A ROW

252
00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:17,590
-Of course.
-Gosh.

253
00:09:17,657 --> 00:09:19,125
He has good energy.

254
00:09:19,191 --> 00:09:20,626
I was scared they might lose.

255
00:09:20,693 --> 00:09:21,727
If they lose…

256
00:09:22,428 --> 00:09:24,697
"Please stop throwing first pitches."

257
00:09:24,764 --> 00:09:25,965
"Do not come anywhere near the ballpark."

258
00:09:26,032 --> 00:09:27,199
"Just go and cook."

259
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:29,735
A CLOSE CALL

260
00:09:29,802 --> 00:09:30,670
"Stay in the kitchen."

261
00:09:30,736 --> 00:09:32,338
After hearing about the first pitch,

262
00:09:32,405 --> 00:09:34,840
I practiced for a month,
about two or three times a week.

263
00:09:34,907 --> 00:09:36,676
-That's amazing.
-I kept pitching.

264
00:09:36,742 --> 00:09:38,177
-I wanted to do well.
-So you practiced.

265
00:09:38,244 --> 00:09:39,779
-Then I hurt my shoulder the day before.
-It happens.

266
00:09:39,845 --> 00:09:41,213
-Goodness.
-Oh, no.

267
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:42,682
That could happen.

268
00:09:42,748 --> 00:09:44,917
That's why he's wearing
pain relief patches.

269
00:09:45,685 --> 00:09:47,119
Too much of anything is bad.

270
00:09:47,186 --> 00:09:50,389
Many of our chefs have gone out
as ceremonial first pitchers.

271
00:09:50,456 --> 00:09:51,891
You two have done it too.

272
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:53,993
-A long time ago.
-We did it once.

273
00:09:54,060 --> 00:09:55,194
-I'm jealous.
-Sam did it too.

274
00:09:55,261 --> 00:09:57,029
-I'm jealous.
-Many of them did it.

275
00:09:57,096 --> 00:09:58,297
Chef Eun-yeong did it too.

276
00:09:58,364 --> 00:10:00,533
-Yes, right.
-I heard about that.

277
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:02,768
Sung-jun and Nam-no are sitting quietly.

278
00:10:03,336 --> 00:10:04,704
I'm going soon.

279
00:10:04,770 --> 00:10:06,505
-What? As a first pitcher?
-You are?

280
00:10:06,572 --> 00:10:08,641
-Yes, for the Giants.
-Unbelievable.

281
00:10:08,708 --> 00:10:10,943
GIANTS INVITED HIM AS THE FIRST PITCHER

282
00:10:11,777 --> 00:10:13,913
-You've never done it?
-Sung-jun?

283
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:15,414
He's a serious baseball fan.

284
00:10:15,481 --> 00:10:17,016
-He loves it.
-I remember last time

285
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:19,285
<i>when Ryu Hyun-jin visited us.</i>

286
00:10:19,352 --> 00:10:21,654
SUNG-JUN SHOWED OFF HIS EAGLES UNIFORM

287
00:10:21,721 --> 00:10:24,290
I've been a fan of the Eagles
since forever.

288
00:10:24,357 --> 00:10:25,891
It's now my 20th year.

289
00:10:25,958 --> 00:10:28,427
Why aren't they inviting you
for the first pitch?

290
00:10:28,494 --> 00:10:29,328
They never do.

291
00:10:30,429 --> 00:10:31,564
He doesn't know why.

292
00:10:31,631 --> 00:10:33,199
-This guy too.
-You didn't say no?

293
00:10:33,265 --> 00:10:34,233
He's a Twins fan too.

294
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:35,901
-He's serious too.
-He's a Twins fan.

295
00:10:36,469 --> 00:10:37,870
GIGGLING

296
00:10:37,937 --> 00:10:39,805
-Yes, he's a Twins fan.
-They never called me.

297
00:10:39,872 --> 00:10:41,173
Make your case.

298
00:10:41,240 --> 00:10:43,242
Actually, Jong-hyuk and I

299
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:45,645
participated as commentators
during the Korean Series last year.

300
00:10:45,711 --> 00:10:47,747
<i>-Hello, I'm Jung Ho-young.</i>
<i>-I'm Lee Jong-hyuk.</i>

301
00:10:48,314 --> 00:10:49,782
CELEBRATED THE TWINS' VICTORY TOGETHER

302
00:10:49,849 --> 00:10:50,816
<i>We won!</i>

303
00:10:50,883 --> 00:10:53,285
TWINS WINS THE 2025 KOREAN SERIES!!!!!

304
00:10:53,352 --> 00:10:55,354
But never as the first pitcher.

305
00:10:55,421 --> 00:10:56,689
Chef Eun-yeong did

306
00:10:56,756 --> 00:10:59,959
an analysis of the chefs
who weren't invited as first pitchers.

307
00:11:00,026 --> 00:11:01,027
An analysis?

308
00:11:01,093 --> 00:11:03,129
-She doesn't even know baseball.
-Why do you think so?

309
00:11:03,195 --> 00:11:05,564
There is only one reason
why they aren't invited.

310
00:11:05,631 --> 00:11:07,099
Why's that?

311
00:11:07,166 --> 00:11:09,568
The two here who have never done it

312
00:11:09,635 --> 00:11:11,203
both have short limbs.

313
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:12,571
COME ON

314
00:11:12,638 --> 00:11:13,472
That's too…

315
00:11:13,539 --> 00:11:17,343
DO THEY HAVE SHORT… LIMBS?

316
00:11:17,410 --> 00:11:19,211
LOSING IT

317
00:11:19,278 --> 00:11:22,548
GENTLE FACE, SAVAGE WORDS

318
00:11:22,615 --> 00:11:23,582
You see…

319
00:11:23,649 --> 00:11:25,151
That was the reason?

320
00:11:25,217 --> 00:11:28,054
You might be wondering
why Nam-no was invited.

321
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:29,555
Although he's a bit lumpy,

322
00:11:29,622 --> 00:11:31,090
he doesn't have short limbs.

323
00:11:31,157 --> 00:11:34,160
NOT SURE IF IT'S A COMPLIMENT…

324
00:11:34,226 --> 00:11:36,028
-He still has long arms?
-But these two

325
00:11:36,095 --> 00:11:38,631
have short limbs,
so the pitch wouldn't look cool.

326
00:11:38,698 --> 00:11:41,067
-That's why they can't invite them.
-Curse me out instead.

327
00:11:41,133 --> 00:11:43,202
Instead of pitching like this,
they'd do this.

328
00:11:43,269 --> 00:11:45,004
This? What is this?

329
00:11:45,071 --> 00:11:47,273
I knew it.
Chef Eun-yeong is the limbs expert.

330
00:11:47,339 --> 00:11:50,543
I'm pretty sharp
when it comes to people's limbs.

331
00:11:50,609 --> 00:11:52,445
I don't think she's completely wrong.

332
00:11:53,179 --> 00:11:55,681
Ho-young and Sung-jun,

333
00:11:55,748 --> 00:11:58,851
why don't you leave a video message
to those affiliated with the teams?

334
00:11:58,918 --> 00:12:00,920
-Starting with the Twins? Ho-young.
-Okay.

335
00:12:00,986 --> 00:12:02,221
I have been…

336
00:12:02,288 --> 00:12:03,255
TO. TWINS ASSOCIATES

337
00:12:03,322 --> 00:12:06,525
…a fan since second grade,
when you were still the Blue Dragons.

338
00:12:06,592 --> 00:12:10,062
-He's an old fan.
-I am always waiting for you.

339
00:12:10,129 --> 00:12:11,931
I'll come anytime, even tomorrow.

340
00:12:13,332 --> 00:12:16,502
He'll clear out his schedule and show up
even if you ask him to come tomorrow.

341
00:12:16,569 --> 00:12:19,338
Sung-jun, why don't you
leave a message to the Eagles?

342
00:12:19,405 --> 00:12:23,075
How much harder must I work
for you to have me?

343
00:12:23,142 --> 00:12:26,545
I did everything whenever you called me
despite my busy schedule last year,

344
00:12:27,113 --> 00:12:29,081
but you never had me as the first pitcher.

345
00:12:29,148 --> 00:12:32,351
I'll appreciate it
if you have me this year.

346
00:12:32,418 --> 00:12:34,186
That was nice and all,

347
00:12:34,253 --> 00:12:36,722
but I want to see
what the pitch would look like

348
00:12:36,789 --> 00:12:38,057
if these short-limbed men did it.

349
00:12:38,124 --> 00:12:39,291
No, we're busy.

350
00:12:39,358 --> 00:12:41,093
SORRY…

351
00:12:41,727 --> 00:12:43,462
-We don't have to go that far.
-I'm sorry.

352
00:12:43,529 --> 00:12:46,332
Soo, do you like any sports? Baseball?

353
00:12:46,398 --> 00:12:47,333
I do.

354
00:12:47,399 --> 00:12:50,236
I'm also an Eagles fan.

355
00:12:50,302 --> 00:12:51,237
I've been a fan for longer.

356
00:12:51,303 --> 00:12:53,072
You lost your chance
to make the first pitch.

357
00:12:53,139 --> 00:12:54,473
It's another failed year.

358
00:12:54,540 --> 00:12:56,742
-He'll get the offer first.
-He'll go first.

359
00:12:56,809 --> 00:12:58,711
He'll pitch for the Eagles first.

360
00:12:58,778 --> 00:13:01,113
Sung-jun can do it next time.

361
00:13:01,180 --> 00:13:04,250
He has to wait longer
because of that question I asked.

362
00:13:04,884 --> 00:13:06,385
WE HOPE YOU GET TO PITCH NEXT YEAR

363
00:13:06,452 --> 00:13:08,287
He's been a huge fan for 20 years.

364
00:13:08,354 --> 00:13:12,424
Now, we're going to look
through Jong-hyuk's fridge.

365
00:13:12,491 --> 00:13:15,361
Last week, Soo's fridge
was something he used alone.

366
00:13:15,427 --> 00:13:17,329
Is this only for you too?

367
00:13:17,396 --> 00:13:18,964
-It's my family fridge.
-His family.

368
00:13:19,031 --> 00:13:21,100
-Four people, right?
-Yes.

369
00:13:21,167 --> 00:13:23,936
I heard you looked at your fridge

370
00:13:24,003 --> 00:13:26,238
and was shocked. What is this about?

371
00:13:26,305 --> 00:13:29,241
When I got the offer
to be a guest on this show,

372
00:13:29,308 --> 00:13:31,510
I shared it with my wife.

373
00:13:31,944 --> 00:13:33,512
She said, "What?"

374
00:13:34,079 --> 00:13:35,181
OUR FRIDGE?

375
00:13:35,247 --> 00:13:36,649
"<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>?"

376
00:13:36,715 --> 00:13:39,752
-It's an emergency.
-And so, she took the fridge

377
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:41,020
and had a rough time with it.

378
00:13:41,086 --> 00:13:42,621
What do you mean by that?

379
00:13:42,688 --> 00:13:43,989
-Did she tidy up?
-That's it.

380
00:13:44,056 --> 00:13:45,758
You'll see once you open it.

381
00:13:45,825 --> 00:13:47,459
TRY TO SPOT HIS WIFE'S TOUCHES

382
00:13:47,526 --> 00:13:49,962
This is Jong-hyuk's fridge.

383
00:13:50,029 --> 00:13:52,231
A fridge for the four family members,

384
00:13:52,298 --> 00:13:54,733
Tak-soo, Joon-su,
the husband, and the wife.

385
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:55,768
One moment.

386
00:13:55,835 --> 00:13:57,203
What are these?

387
00:13:57,269 --> 00:13:59,104
-He's growing green onions.
-Do you grow these?

388
00:13:59,738 --> 00:14:02,041
Is this also something she staged?

389
00:14:02,107 --> 00:14:03,275
-No.
-"Staged"?

390
00:14:03,342 --> 00:14:06,045
Those are Tak-soo's.

391
00:14:06,111 --> 00:14:07,980
He suddenly began to grow green onions.

392
00:14:08,047 --> 00:14:09,915
-Tak-soo is growing these?
-Yes, I was surprised.

393
00:14:09,982 --> 00:14:12,985
So if we use these up to here
and put them in water,

394
00:14:13,052 --> 00:14:14,753
-do they grow like this?
-Yes.

395
00:14:14,820 --> 00:14:16,388
Cut it up to there

396
00:14:16,455 --> 00:14:18,858
and fill it with enough water
so that it soaks the roots.

397
00:14:18,924 --> 00:14:20,125
Then you can keep eating it.

398
00:14:20,192 --> 00:14:21,360
-That's true.
-Yes.

399
00:14:21,427 --> 00:14:23,362
Some people plant those
and grow them for food.

400
00:14:23,429 --> 00:14:26,832
He grows these, works part-time,
and has to practice acting too.

401
00:14:26,899 --> 00:14:29,301
-He's resourceful.
-He's growing green onions.

402
00:14:29,368 --> 00:14:31,704
Your eldest son is something.

403
00:14:31,770 --> 00:14:32,738
He's a domestic whiz.

404
00:14:32,805 --> 00:14:34,573
What if he starts raising cows too?

405
00:14:36,275 --> 00:14:37,843
I'm all for it.

406
00:14:37,910 --> 00:14:39,345
All right, then.

407
00:14:39,411 --> 00:14:41,680
Let's take a good look at his fridge.

408
00:14:41,747 --> 00:14:44,183
-We present Jong-hyuk's fridge!
-Fridge!

409
00:14:45,217 --> 00:14:46,986
WOW

410
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:48,254
-Fridge!
-Fridge!

411
00:14:48,320 --> 00:14:49,655
PRESENTING JONG-HYUK'S FRIDGE

412
00:14:49,722 --> 00:14:51,056
-This is insane.
-It's full.

413
00:14:51,123 --> 00:14:54,326
NEATLY ORGANIZED AND WELL-STOCKED

414
00:14:54,393 --> 00:14:55,628
AUTOMATIC APPLAUSE

415
00:14:55,694 --> 00:14:56,762
Bravo!

416
00:14:57,763 --> 00:14:59,198
A STANDING OVATION

417
00:14:59,865 --> 00:15:01,734
GREAT WORK, WIFEY

418
00:15:01,800 --> 00:15:03,869
It must've been so much work!

419
00:15:03,936 --> 00:15:05,704
-Goodness.
-It's so neatly organized.

420
00:15:05,771 --> 00:15:07,973
Do you see traces of my wife's tears?

421
00:15:08,540 --> 00:15:10,209
WE CAN SEE IT

422
00:15:10,276 --> 00:15:12,411
-There are traces of her…
-These are all brand-new!

423
00:15:12,978 --> 00:15:16,482
-All these containers are new!
-She bought all these.

424
00:15:16,548 --> 00:15:18,083
She must've bought new ones

425
00:15:18,150 --> 00:15:20,119
-and moved them.
-Of course.

426
00:15:20,185 --> 00:15:22,888
She probably wiped off the edges too.

427
00:15:22,955 --> 00:15:25,958
Wait, aren't you supposed to come
with your fridge as is?

428
00:15:26,025 --> 00:15:27,893
That's what we aim to do.

429
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:30,663
We aren't allowed
to stage the fridge, are we?

430
00:15:30,729 --> 00:15:32,598
PREVIOUSLY, DURING HIS FRIDGE PRESENTATION

431
00:15:32,665 --> 00:15:35,334
My family fridge has too many ingredients.

432
00:15:35,401 --> 00:15:37,803
Even I could do that.

433
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:40,539
ON TOP OF THAT, HE BROUGHT
ONLY HIS PERSONAL INGREDIENTS

434
00:15:40,940 --> 00:15:43,676
-That's why I brought everything as is.
-That's our intention.

435
00:15:43,742 --> 00:15:47,112
But there are times
when the wife feels a bit of pressure.

436
00:15:47,179 --> 00:15:49,214
-She's in charge of housekeeping.
-When it happens,

437
00:15:49,281 --> 00:15:50,849
we can't stop them.

438
00:15:50,916 --> 00:15:53,485
It's not that they added more ingredients.

439
00:15:53,552 --> 00:15:55,955
-She organized it and made it neater.
-Yes, she cleaned it.

440
00:15:56,021 --> 00:15:57,723
Our fridge is so neat now.

441
00:15:57,790 --> 00:15:59,458
A NEVER-BEFORE-SEEN FRIDGE

442
00:15:59,525 --> 00:16:00,693
It was great motivation!

443
00:16:00,759 --> 00:16:02,294
I should be here more often.

444
00:16:03,796 --> 00:16:05,264
Once every six months.

445
00:16:05,931 --> 00:16:08,000
Gosh, it must've been rough.

446
00:16:08,067 --> 00:16:09,601
-It must've been.
-Look at this.

447
00:16:09,668 --> 00:16:11,170
Starting with the first shelf.

448
00:16:11,236 --> 00:16:13,605
What's this? Squid? Cuttlefish.

449
00:16:13,672 --> 00:16:14,773
-Cuttlefish?
-Cuttlefish.

450
00:16:14,840 --> 00:16:17,076
In the unit one floor beneath us lives

451
00:16:17,142 --> 00:16:18,978
the comedian Kang Sung-bum,

452
00:16:19,044 --> 00:16:20,245
and he loves to fish.

453
00:16:20,312 --> 00:16:23,549
-He caught that and gave it to me.
-He caught this?

454
00:16:23,615 --> 00:16:26,085
-Goodness, look at these.
-What are those?

455
00:16:26,151 --> 00:16:28,387
-Manila clams. This is a flounder.
-Manila clams.

456
00:16:28,454 --> 00:16:30,656
Also, webfoot octopus and cutlassfish.

457
00:16:30,723 --> 00:16:33,058
I prefer ingredients that are in season.

458
00:16:33,125 --> 00:16:36,795
Flounders and octopuses are
all full of roe, and they're delicious.

459
00:16:36,862 --> 00:16:40,065
Any other in-season ingredients
you've been enjoying?

460
00:16:40,132 --> 00:16:43,068
-I like spring <i>namul</i>, spring greens.
-Spring greens.

461
00:16:43,135 --> 00:16:45,804
-I got shepherd's purse and wild chives.
-Shepherd's purse.

462
00:16:45,871 --> 00:16:47,606
-You do.
-Wild chives, shepherd's purse.

463
00:16:47,673 --> 00:16:51,276
I got it straight from Ganghwado Island
from my aunt.

464
00:16:51,343 --> 00:16:53,045
It hasn't even been five days.

465
00:16:53,412 --> 00:16:54,246
TOTALLY FRESH

466
00:16:54,813 --> 00:16:55,748
I haven't even washed those.

467
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:57,950
Are these <i>dureup</i>, angelica-tree shoots?

468
00:16:58,017 --> 00:16:59,318
-Spinach.
-<i>Dureup</i>?

469
00:16:59,385 --> 00:17:01,387
-It's spinach.
-It's spinach.

470
00:17:01,453 --> 00:17:04,723
My father-in-law has a spinach farm,

471
00:17:04,790 --> 00:17:05,858
and he grew too many.

472
00:17:05,924 --> 00:17:08,961
He gave some out to everyone,
so we got a huge bag too.

473
00:17:09,028 --> 00:17:12,164
-I found <i>dureup</i> too.
-You did? He likes in-season ingredients.

474
00:17:12,231 --> 00:17:14,099
Wait, I don't see any meat.

475
00:17:14,166 --> 00:17:16,335
I probably have a little,
but whenever we get some,

476
00:17:17,069 --> 00:17:17,936
my kids eat them all.

477
00:17:18,971 --> 00:17:20,773
-I found one.
-This is the only one.

478
00:17:20,839 --> 00:17:22,074
A pack of bulgogi.

479
00:17:22,141 --> 00:17:23,942
-It never lasts, does it?
-Never.

480
00:17:24,009 --> 00:17:26,011
-They must eat like a horse at that age.
-Yes.

481
00:17:26,078 --> 00:17:28,781
Goodness. Anyone can see
that this is a new container.

482
00:17:28,847 --> 00:17:30,149
Brand-new.

483
00:17:30,215 --> 00:17:31,950
A new container that smells like plastic.

484
00:17:32,918 --> 00:17:34,053
The size fits perfectly.

485
00:17:34,486 --> 00:17:35,754
GREEN ONION IN PERFECT SIZES

486
00:17:35,821 --> 00:17:37,222
Did your wife prep these?

487
00:17:37,656 --> 00:17:38,957
I can sense the pressure on her.

488
00:17:39,024 --> 00:17:40,793
NEVER-BEFORE-SEEN FORMATION

489
00:17:40,859 --> 00:17:42,261
Wait, as we speak…

490
00:17:42,861 --> 00:17:44,997
DID YOU FIND SOMETHING RARE?

491
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:46,231
We didn't see it last time!

492
00:17:46,298 --> 00:17:47,966
-I found cilantro!
-He has cilantro!

493
00:17:48,033 --> 00:17:50,169
Jong-hyuk's family has cilantro!

494
00:17:50,235 --> 00:17:51,403
GO SOO & GOSU
A RARE TWO-SHOT

495
00:17:51,470 --> 00:17:53,205
I love cilantro.

496
00:17:53,272 --> 00:17:54,573
I see. He likes cilantro.

497
00:17:54,640 --> 00:17:55,774
I'm a huge fan of yours.

498
00:17:57,076 --> 00:17:59,578
-You like Go Soo and <i>gosu</i>.
-Yes, both.

499
00:17:59,645 --> 00:18:00,879
How do you eat it?

500
00:18:00,946 --> 00:18:02,381
I throw it into <i>ramyeon</i>.

501
00:18:02,815 --> 00:18:04,216
GOSU RAMYEON

502
00:18:04,283 --> 00:18:07,853
-That sounds good.
-I once traveled to Vietnam,

503
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:09,488
-and when I had pho there,
-Yes?

504
00:18:09,555 --> 00:18:13,525
-I added more cilantro than the noodles.
-That's good.

505
00:18:13,592 --> 00:18:14,860
-You must love it.
-I do.

506
00:18:14,927 --> 00:18:17,429
-Does the scent not bother you?
-No.

507
00:18:17,496 --> 00:18:19,264
When I eat something like rockfish soup,

508
00:18:19,331 --> 00:18:20,899
I add lots of <i>sansho </i>pepper powder.

509
00:18:20,966 --> 00:18:22,034
-<i>Sansho</i>?
-<i>Sansho</i>.

510
00:18:22,101 --> 00:18:23,502
-And Korean mint.
-Yes, Korean mint.

511
00:18:23,569 --> 00:18:24,670
I like to add lots of those.

512
00:18:24,736 --> 00:18:26,338
I get disappointed
when they don't have it.

513
00:18:27,306 --> 00:18:29,608
When I ask for it at a<i> maeun-tang</i> place,
a fish soup place, and hear,

514
00:18:29,675 --> 00:18:31,043
"We don't have anything like that."

515
00:18:31,810 --> 00:18:32,711
SIGH

516
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:35,647
THE FACE OF A DISAPPOINTED MAN

517
00:18:35,714 --> 00:18:37,416
You were just getting excited,

518
00:18:37,483 --> 00:18:40,085
-so if they don't have it…
-"How could they not have it?"

519
00:18:40,652 --> 00:18:42,087
TODAY'S DISHES BETTER HAVE A STRONG SCENT

520
00:18:42,154 --> 00:18:43,722
Make sure you humor his taste.

521
00:18:43,789 --> 00:18:46,058
-He hates missing an essential ingredient.
-I feel him.

522
00:18:46,125 --> 00:18:46,992
That's right.

523
00:18:47,059 --> 00:18:48,494
There are all kinds of side dishes.

524
00:18:48,560 --> 00:18:51,096
-There are lots.
-Look at all these.

525
00:18:51,163 --> 00:18:52,564
My gosh. Look.

526
00:18:52,631 --> 00:18:54,666
I'm sorry, but if you seem too surprised,

527
00:18:54,733 --> 00:18:57,870
my wife will feel burdened at home,
so tone it down.

528
00:18:57,936 --> 00:18:59,505
Did she make all these?

529
00:18:59,571 --> 00:19:00,939
Yes, for now.

530
00:19:01,006 --> 00:19:03,108
-"For now"?
-No, it's…

531
00:19:03,175 --> 00:19:04,977
I'm saying
she moved it to those containers.

532
00:19:05,043 --> 00:19:06,445
-Into the containers.
-Just this time.

533
00:19:06,512 --> 00:19:09,414
It's been about a week
since she made those side dishes,

534
00:19:09,481 --> 00:19:10,983
and they're already halfway done.

535
00:19:11,550 --> 00:19:12,718
My kids eat everything.

536
00:19:12,784 --> 00:19:14,653
-They eat it up quickly.
-Yes, you'll run out.

537
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:18,991
I also remember Jong-hyuk as a good cook.

538
00:19:19,057 --> 00:19:20,259
-I'm good.
-You were popular

539
00:19:20,325 --> 00:19:22,494
among the kids during
<i>Dad! Where Are We Going?</i> shoots.

540
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:24,296
-I was.
-What did you make back then?

541
00:19:24,363 --> 00:19:25,697
Plum noodles.

542
00:19:25,764 --> 00:19:27,332
-It sounds good.
-It sounds good.

543
00:19:27,399 --> 00:19:30,002
Do you still cook for your kids at home?

544
00:19:30,068 --> 00:19:33,772
I make dishes like kimchi fried rice
and spicy noodles with whelk.

545
00:19:33,839 --> 00:19:35,174
Do they love it?

546
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:36,942
They go crazy and finish everything,

547
00:19:37,009 --> 00:19:38,644
even after the dishes turn cold.

548
00:19:38,710 --> 00:19:40,579
-Those still taste good.
-Look how big they are.

549
00:19:40,646 --> 00:19:44,483
I'm sure Jong-hyuk's dishes played a part.

550
00:19:44,550 --> 00:19:47,786
Goodness, look at these.
You can see that he loves to drink.

551
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:49,054
FILLED WITH ALCOHOL

552
00:19:49,121 --> 00:19:50,956
-Beer and soju.
-He has the red caps.

553
00:19:51,023 --> 00:19:54,059
When I drink, I start off with <i>somaek</i>.

554
00:19:54,126 --> 00:19:56,328
-These two.
-That's my first drink.

555
00:19:56,395 --> 00:19:59,298
Then I go back to soju,
but when I get thirsty, I sip on beer.

556
00:19:59,364 --> 00:20:00,799
You sip on beer to quench your thirst?

557
00:20:00,866 --> 00:20:02,634
-Instead of water.
-He has a routine.

558
00:20:02,701 --> 00:20:04,870
He has oriental raisin drinks here,
the hangover cure.

559
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:07,773
Life is all about creating a problem,
then finding a solution.

560
00:20:08,340 --> 00:20:11,376
CREATE A HANGOVER AND DRINK THE SOLUTION

561
00:20:11,443 --> 00:20:13,111
How do you cure your hangovers?

562
00:20:13,178 --> 00:20:15,681
I drink clear soup I have at home,

563
00:20:15,747 --> 00:20:17,249
like <i>gomtang</i>, beef bone soup.

564
00:20:17,316 --> 00:20:18,584
-Clear soup.
-Yes.

565
00:20:18,650 --> 00:20:21,820
-Or clear fish soup. That's what I prefer.
-Clear fish soup, <i>jiri</i>.

566
00:20:21,887 --> 00:20:24,156
-Something refreshing.
-Refreshing soup.

567
00:20:24,223 --> 00:20:25,724
What's this?

568
00:20:25,791 --> 00:20:29,027
-Whoa, you froze tangerines?
-Yes, it's because

569
00:20:29,094 --> 00:20:31,597
tangerines ripen too fast
and become moldy.

570
00:20:31,663 --> 00:20:33,732
-And turn soft. It's a shame.
-Yes, after a while.

571
00:20:33,799 --> 00:20:35,867
We never finish them,
so Joon-su must've done that.

572
00:20:35,934 --> 00:20:37,869
-Joon-su did this?
-Goodness.

573
00:20:37,936 --> 00:20:39,137
These are great frozen.

574
00:20:39,204 --> 00:20:41,707
I'm dying to know when he'll eat those.

575
00:20:42,274 --> 00:20:43,308
ONLY STORED, NEVER CONSUMED…

576
00:20:43,375 --> 00:20:45,244
-How will he eat those?
-He just threw those in?

577
00:20:45,310 --> 00:20:46,912
-I don't know.
-He doesn't eat it often?

578
00:20:46,979 --> 00:20:49,815
That's been in the freezer
for at least six months.

579
00:20:49,881 --> 00:20:51,717
Is Joon-su into cooking too?

580
00:20:51,783 --> 00:20:53,385
Joon-su?

581
00:20:53,452 --> 00:20:56,054
One day, I found something milky white
in a tiny container.

582
00:20:56,121 --> 00:20:56,989
I asked him,

583
00:20:57,055 --> 00:21:00,092
and he said it was cooled oil he set aside

584
00:21:00,158 --> 00:21:01,426
after grilling pork belly.

585
00:21:02,027 --> 00:21:04,363
-Lard?
-Lard.

586
00:21:04,429 --> 00:21:06,131
-Is it called lard?
-It's called lard.

587
00:21:06,198 --> 00:21:09,768
He adds some
when he warms up frozen fried rice.

588
00:21:09,835 --> 00:21:11,503
-That's good.
-He knows good food.

589
00:21:11,570 --> 00:21:13,705
It's because he has seen his dad cook.

590
00:21:13,772 --> 00:21:15,974
These are all soups.

591
00:21:16,041 --> 00:21:16,942
Probably gifts.

592
00:21:17,009 --> 00:21:20,312
<i>Budae-jjigae</i>, sausage stew,
<i>sundae-guk</i>, and <i>gomtang</i>.

593
00:21:20,379 --> 00:21:22,214
-They're great with drinks.
-Do you like soup?

594
00:21:22,281 --> 00:21:24,549
-Yes, I like soup.
-He must like soup.

595
00:21:24,616 --> 00:21:26,351
You seem to prefer Korean food.

596
00:21:26,418 --> 00:21:29,588
I like all food,
but I eat Korean food the most often.

597
00:21:29,655 --> 00:21:32,124
That was all for Jong-hyuk's fridge!

598
00:21:32,190 --> 00:21:34,626
FINISHED CHECKING OUT JONG-HYUK'S FRIDGE

599
00:21:34,693 --> 00:21:37,529
What kind of dishes is he looking for?

600
00:21:37,596 --> 00:21:39,665
Let's find out his orders.

601
00:21:39,731 --> 00:21:40,699
Today's orders.

602
00:21:41,333 --> 00:21:43,168
-Season's Dignity.
-Season's Dignity.

603
00:21:43,235 --> 00:21:45,137
-Just like <i>A Gentleman's Dignity</i>.
-Yes.

604
00:21:45,203 --> 00:21:46,972
Season's Dignity.
What do you mean by that?

605
00:21:47,039 --> 00:21:50,509
I want something perfect for the season
made with in-season ingredients,

606
00:21:50,575 --> 00:21:54,279
-something refreshing and delicious.
-Something perfect in this season?

607
00:21:54,346 --> 00:21:55,414
That's Season's Dignity.

608
00:21:55,480 --> 00:21:57,482
-And I have all the ingredients.
-You do.

609
00:21:58,450 --> 00:22:01,286
<i>You saw his seafood and spring greens.</i>

610
00:22:01,353 --> 00:22:02,954
What's the second order?

611
00:22:03,021 --> 00:22:04,389
-Red Cap's Dignity?
-The second order.

612
00:22:05,524 --> 00:22:08,026
-Hangover.
-Hangover, Where Are You Going?

613
00:22:08,093 --> 00:22:10,362
-Not <i>Dad! Where Are We Going?</i>
-Hangover, Where Are You Going?

614
00:22:10,429 --> 00:22:12,998
I already mentioned
that I'm into clear soup.

615
00:22:13,065 --> 00:22:15,233
I want something so good
that although I have a hangover,

616
00:22:15,300 --> 00:22:17,869
I still find it to be a waste
to eat without a drink.

617
00:22:17,936 --> 00:22:19,871
Something that makes me go,
"One soju, please."

618
00:22:19,938 --> 00:22:21,540
-With a hangover?
-Something to make you say that.

619
00:22:21,606 --> 00:22:23,809
A dish that'll make you drink
as you cure your hangover.

620
00:22:23,875 --> 00:22:25,577
-Yes, that's it.
-Something like that.

621
00:22:25,644 --> 00:22:27,212
He can't just cure his hangover.

622
00:22:27,779 --> 00:22:30,248
It needs to turn into another bar snack.

623
00:22:30,315 --> 00:22:34,219
The four who didn't go last week
can join one of these two rounds.

624
00:22:34,286 --> 00:22:36,955
Everyone is reading each other's faces.

625
00:22:37,022 --> 00:22:38,390
Then I'll go first.

626
00:22:38,457 --> 00:22:41,159
I also like to drink
and am good at curing hangovers,

627
00:22:41,226 --> 00:22:42,361
so Hangover, Where Are You Going?

628
00:22:42,427 --> 00:22:44,096
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

629
00:22:44,162 --> 00:22:45,197
All right, then.

630
00:22:45,263 --> 00:22:46,298
I'll join.

631
00:22:46,365 --> 00:22:50,369
Anything related to drinks,
be it a bar snack or a hangover cure…

632
00:22:50,435 --> 00:22:51,269
He's a tough one.

633
00:22:51,336 --> 00:22:53,905
…I'd be disappointed if you leave me out.

634
00:22:53,972 --> 00:22:56,274
I'll go against Ho-young.
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

635
00:22:56,341 --> 00:22:57,576
Poong is in.

636
00:22:57,642 --> 00:23:00,545
Ho-young and Poong
will fill the same order.

637
00:23:00,612 --> 00:23:03,515
This means the first round
is automatically decided.

638
00:23:03,582 --> 00:23:05,317
-Automatic.
-Jong-won and Eun-yeong.

639
00:23:05,384 --> 00:23:06,818
-Okay.
-Let's do Season's Dignity.

640
00:23:06,885 --> 00:23:09,121
-Yes, let's do that.
-We'll make in-season dishes.

641
00:23:09,187 --> 00:23:10,856
-Season's Dignity.
-Okay.

642
00:23:10,922 --> 00:23:15,060
Jong-won and Eun-yeong
automatically take Season's Dignity.

643
00:23:15,127 --> 00:23:16,962
Let's begin with Season's Dignity.

644
00:23:17,028 --> 00:23:20,432
Let's begin Jong-won and Eun-yeong's
15-minute cook-off!

645
00:23:20,999 --> 00:23:23,101
THE IN-SEASON INGREDIENT ROUND BEGINS NOW

646
00:23:23,168 --> 00:23:27,539
<i>This is the first round played</i>
<i>with ingredients from Jong-hyuk's fridge.</i>

647
00:23:27,606 --> 00:23:29,875
Here to reestablish discipline
in the world of culinary arts,

648
00:23:29,941 --> 00:23:31,943
the head of the disciplinary committee,
Chef Son Jong-won,

649
00:23:33,211 --> 00:23:35,647
versus Chef Park Eun-yeong,
here to discipline Ho-young…

650
00:23:35,714 --> 00:23:38,417
-Wait, why me?
-…as the leader of the dance club.

651
00:23:38,483 --> 00:23:40,252
-They're the dance club?
-Yes.

652
00:23:40,318 --> 00:23:42,154
When did he become part
of the disciplinary committee?

653
00:23:42,220 --> 00:23:46,124
Remember the one-versus-three
tag team round?

654
00:23:46,191 --> 00:23:48,760
SON JONG-WON VS. THE 3 MEMBERS OF HURTRIX

655
00:23:49,060 --> 00:23:51,062
SON JONG-WON WINS

656
00:23:51,329 --> 00:23:54,132
HE SUCCESSFULLY DISCIPLINED THE YOUNG GUNS

657
00:23:54,566 --> 00:23:56,701
THE ROUND ENDED IN A SCUFFLE

658
00:23:56,768 --> 00:23:59,805
-He showed them who the boss was.
-We were whipped.

659
00:23:59,871 --> 00:24:03,008
Actually, Chef Jong-won had been waiting

660
00:24:03,074 --> 00:24:05,911
for Eun-yeong to come at him
without the Tubby Twins.

661
00:24:06,878 --> 00:24:08,013
Why is that?

662
00:24:08,079 --> 00:24:10,682
-At the end of last year… Yes.
-The championship match?

663
00:24:10,749 --> 00:24:13,552
I lost to Chef Eun-yeong
in the first round.

664
00:24:13,618 --> 00:24:15,921
<i>Gosh, Jong-won has been eliminated.</i>

665
00:24:15,987 --> 00:24:17,022
ELIMINATED IN THE FIRST ROUND!

666
00:24:17,088 --> 00:24:18,156
OUT FOR REVENGE

667
00:24:18,223 --> 00:24:19,191
Yes, that happened.

668
00:24:19,257 --> 00:24:21,426
I've already set Chef Jong-won back

669
00:24:21,493 --> 00:24:23,628
during the championship, haven't I?

670
00:24:23,695 --> 00:24:27,265
These days, he's been
gaining momentum yet again,

671
00:24:27,332 --> 00:24:29,634
so I had been thinking
of throwing a wet blanket over him.

672
00:24:29,701 --> 00:24:31,169
HIGHLY SPIRITED

673
00:24:31,236 --> 00:24:33,505
If you win today,
you'll become the Jong-won killer.

674
00:24:33,572 --> 00:24:35,774
-Yes.
-You'll have him in the palm of your hand.

675
00:24:35,841 --> 00:24:37,542
Although Chef Jong-won

676
00:24:37,609 --> 00:24:40,312
had been looking for a chance
to get his revenge,

677
00:24:40,378 --> 00:24:44,216
it also seemed like
he had become Eun-yeong's fan.

678
00:24:44,282 --> 00:24:47,219
She made a huge issue,
thanks to her dances.

679
00:24:47,285 --> 00:24:48,687
THE TALK OF THE TOWN

680
00:24:48,753 --> 00:24:50,689
I think everything began

681
00:24:50,755 --> 00:24:52,757
during the cook-off against Poong

682
00:24:52,824 --> 00:24:54,659
when she did the motion for strikeout.

683
00:24:54,726 --> 00:24:56,361
I believe that was the beginning.

684
00:24:57,128 --> 00:24:58,430
THIS GESTURE STARTED IT ALL

685
00:24:58,497 --> 00:25:00,098
HER LUNACY HAD BEEN UNLEASHED

686
00:25:00,165 --> 00:25:01,967
AND THAT'S HOW JONG-WON BECAME A FAN

687
00:25:02,033 --> 00:25:03,201
She's insane.

688
00:25:03,268 --> 00:25:04,336
She really is.

689
00:25:04,402 --> 00:25:06,438
Everyone called her crazy,

690
00:25:06,505 --> 00:25:08,974
-but I thought she was a genius.
-That she's doing well.

691
00:25:09,040 --> 00:25:11,776
If someone had nipped the bud,

692
00:25:11,843 --> 00:25:14,312
she couldn't have done
anything after that.

693
00:25:14,379 --> 00:25:16,348
I think it's all thanks to my support.

694
00:25:16,414 --> 00:25:18,884
He claims
that he kept Eun-yeong's spirits up.

695
00:25:19,451 --> 00:25:21,353
I don't think I can agree to that.

696
00:25:22,754 --> 00:25:25,056
-Not that far?
-He did show me support,

697
00:25:25,123 --> 00:25:28,059
but I came this far
thanks to my personal talent.

698
00:25:28,126 --> 00:25:29,427
"Don't try to ride my coattails."

699
00:25:29,494 --> 00:25:30,762
It's her personal talent.

700
00:25:30,829 --> 00:25:33,164
Please have a speck of modesty.

701
00:25:33,231 --> 00:25:35,567
I guess you appreciated
the way she worked hard.

702
00:25:35,634 --> 00:25:37,802
I also try as hard as I can,

703
00:25:37,869 --> 00:25:40,672
but sometimes I think,
"Does she have to try that hard?"

704
00:25:40,739 --> 00:25:42,207
And I reflected on myself.

705
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:43,742
-Like, "What am I doing?"
-I can try harder.

706
00:25:44,709 --> 00:25:46,077
This is my personal take,

707
00:25:46,144 --> 00:25:48,146
but one day,
Jong-won will start dancing too.

708
00:25:48,547 --> 00:25:50,615
WILL HE?

709
00:25:50,682 --> 00:25:52,651
He'll dance once before the year is up.

710
00:25:52,717 --> 00:25:54,619
-He'll have to do it.
-He'll have to.

711
00:25:54,686 --> 00:25:55,921
He can't help but do it.

712
00:25:55,987 --> 00:25:59,791
Anyway, Chef Eun-yeong, why have you
become so serious about dancing?

713
00:25:59,858 --> 00:26:03,161
I recently began to run my own restaurant,

714
00:26:03,228 --> 00:26:05,931
and my life has become quite difficult.

715
00:26:05,997 --> 00:26:08,733
It made me realize
that dancing was much easier.

716
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:11,303
After I had that thought,
I began to dance even more.

717
00:26:11,369 --> 00:26:12,971
Where can we see you dance?

718
00:26:13,038 --> 00:26:15,073
-Look forward to it today.
-You'll see soon.

719
00:26:15,140 --> 00:26:19,511
You're about to cook for Jong-hyuk,

720
00:26:19,578 --> 00:26:20,745
who loves in-season ingredients.

721
00:26:20,812 --> 00:26:24,082
Chef Jong-won said,
"Using in-season ingredients

722
00:26:24,149 --> 00:26:25,884
to make a Chinese dish

723
00:26:25,951 --> 00:26:28,186
would be quite disadvantageous,
don't you think?"

724
00:26:29,020 --> 00:26:31,456
He just said that in passing.

725
00:26:31,523 --> 00:26:33,124
I agree that Chef Jong-won

726
00:26:33,191 --> 00:26:35,594
probably has a higher understanding
of the in-season ingredients.

727
00:26:35,660 --> 00:26:39,431
However, I have an advantage
when it comes to this cook-off.

728
00:26:39,497 --> 00:26:42,000
I have an old dude's appetite,
just as Jong-hyuk does.

729
00:26:42,067 --> 00:26:43,201
However, as we all know,

730
00:26:43,268 --> 00:26:45,570
-Chef Jong-won is a guy who works out.
-Right.

731
00:26:45,637 --> 00:26:48,139
-All he eats here are bananas and eggs.
-She's right.

732
00:26:48,206 --> 00:26:49,975
-Eggs.
-That's all he ever eats.

733
00:26:50,041 --> 00:26:51,843
-I would never.
-He doesn't know how an old dude eats.

734
00:26:51,910 --> 00:26:54,112
So I believe
I have an advantage in this cook-off.

735
00:26:54,179 --> 00:26:57,282
-I like that old dude's appetite.
-He likes it.

736
00:26:58,116 --> 00:27:00,151
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS:
DUREUP, WILD CHIVE, SHEPHERD'S PURSE

737
00:27:00,218 --> 00:27:02,287
CILANTRO, CHIVE, BELL PEPPER,
CUTTLEFISH, WEBFOOT OCTOPUS, AND MORE

738
00:27:02,354 --> 00:27:05,557
What's the fresh seasonal dish
you're making, Jong-won?

739
00:27:05,624 --> 00:27:07,659
I don't think
there's anything more extravagant

740
00:27:07,726 --> 00:27:09,094
than enjoying seasonal dishes.

741
00:27:09,160 --> 00:27:11,863
Among the seasons,
I prepared something for spring.

742
00:27:11,930 --> 00:27:14,366
And for the first time on the show,
I'll consider the next round

743
00:27:14,432 --> 00:27:16,868
and let you grab a little drink
while you enjoy

744
00:27:16,935 --> 00:27:18,503
-the seasonal dish.
-The next round?

745
00:27:18,570 --> 00:27:20,105
-My dish is called…
-Called?

746
00:27:20,171 --> 00:27:22,307
…I Must Want to Be Drunk on Spring Today.

747
00:27:22,374 --> 00:27:23,808
-I see.
-I Must Want to Be Drunk.

748
00:27:23,875 --> 00:27:26,711
In the next round,
he'll eat something to cure a hangover,

749
00:27:26,778 --> 00:27:28,313
so he'll link the two.

750
00:27:28,380 --> 00:27:29,948
TRYING TO GET HIM DRUNK ALREADY

751
00:27:30,015 --> 00:27:32,484
Jong-hyuk reminded me of a warrior.

752
00:27:32,550 --> 00:27:33,818
-A warrior.
-A bodyguard.

753
00:27:33,885 --> 00:27:35,687
Like a royal warrior.

754
00:27:35,754 --> 00:27:38,990
I imagined a royal warrior
who returned from war,

755
00:27:39,057 --> 00:27:41,059
sitting alone
with a table of drinks and food

756
00:27:41,126 --> 00:27:42,927
and enjoying a drink.

757
00:27:42,994 --> 00:27:44,029
I prepared three dishes.

758
00:27:44,095 --> 00:27:45,397
Three dishes.

759
00:27:45,463 --> 00:27:46,865
First, deep-fried <i>dureup</i>.

760
00:27:46,931 --> 00:27:49,067
-<i>Dureup</i>.
-That can't be not good.

761
00:27:49,134 --> 00:27:52,170
I'll make crispy <i>dureup</i>
with some shrimp filling.

762
00:27:52,237 --> 00:27:53,171
Next, noodles.

763
00:27:53,238 --> 00:27:54,506
-Noodles?
-Noodles?

764
00:27:54,572 --> 00:27:57,709
I'll use different spring greens
to make the noodles.

765
00:27:57,776 --> 00:27:59,611
And thirdly, I prepared <i>ganghoe</i>.

766
00:27:59,678 --> 00:28:00,745
I'll use cuttlefish

767
00:28:00,812 --> 00:28:03,615
-and wrap it with chives to make that.
-It sounds good.

768
00:28:03,682 --> 00:28:05,950
-The rolled dish. Dipped in <i>chogochujang</i>.
-It's good with <i>chogochujang</i>.

769
00:28:06,017 --> 00:28:06,985
GANGHOE: BOILED SEAFOOD DISH

770
00:28:07,052 --> 00:28:09,721
You're giving him a nice taste of spring.

771
00:28:10,555 --> 00:28:12,357
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS:
MANILA CLAM, FLOUNDER

772
00:28:12,424 --> 00:28:14,726
WEBFOOT OCTOPUS, DUREUP, CHIVE,
YUJA CHEONG, PERILLA OIL, AND MORE

773
00:28:14,793 --> 00:28:17,629
Chef Eun-yeong is up against him today.
What are you making?

774
00:28:17,696 --> 00:28:19,464
The dish that I prepared today…

775
00:28:20,298 --> 00:28:21,866
Does it use a lot of <i>dureup</i>?

776
00:28:21,933 --> 00:28:24,969
Fresh seasonal seafood
is often used in Chinese food

777
00:28:25,036 --> 00:28:27,872
to serve a distinguished guest.

778
00:28:27,939 --> 00:28:30,608
Today, I'll steam flounder,
top it with <i>dureup</i>,

779
00:28:30,675 --> 00:28:33,344
and pour hot oil over the dish

780
00:28:33,411 --> 00:28:36,414
to make it as tender as the fish can get.

781
00:28:36,481 --> 00:28:37,682
WOW

782
00:28:37,749 --> 00:28:39,417
Also, I'll use webfoot octopus roe

783
00:28:39,484 --> 00:28:43,188
and make seafood soup
you can enjoy on the side.

784
00:28:43,254 --> 00:28:46,691
Let's begin the 15-minute cook-off now.

785
00:28:46,758 --> 00:28:49,561
Why do I feel more anxious than them?

786
00:28:49,627 --> 00:28:52,263
ALSO GETTING ANXIOUS

787
00:28:52,330 --> 00:28:54,232
Currently alone in first place,

788
00:28:54,299 --> 00:28:56,901
the man who has found his season
on this show, Chef Son Jong-won.

789
00:28:56,968 --> 00:28:58,837
Currently first place in lunacy,

790
00:28:58,903 --> 00:28:59,738
HEHE

791
00:28:59,804 --> 00:29:03,441
the woman who has found her prime
on this show, Chef Park Eun-yeong.

792
00:29:03,508 --> 00:29:06,044
Which one of them will show
the Season's Dignity?

793
00:29:06,111 --> 00:29:09,547
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

794
00:29:09,614 --> 00:29:10,448
Let's go!

795
00:29:10,515 --> 00:29:13,384
PEEKING INTO THE 15-MINUTE COOKING VLOG

796
00:29:13,451 --> 00:29:15,620
The two born fighters are in this battle.

797
00:29:15,687 --> 00:29:16,821
MANILA CLAMS

798
00:29:16,888 --> 00:29:20,258
-Chef Eun-yeong begins with the broth.
-She's boiling Manila clams.

799
00:29:20,325 --> 00:29:22,227
-She's using Manila clams.
-The broth.

800
00:29:22,293 --> 00:29:23,962
There's the flounder.

801
00:29:24,028 --> 00:29:27,265
-Flounder with roe.
-Flounder with roe?

802
00:29:27,332 --> 00:29:29,601
She makes cuts on the fish.

803
00:29:29,667 --> 00:29:32,003
-It's the fatty kind of flounder.
-It looks good.

804
00:29:32,737 --> 00:29:33,738
-Will she grill it?
-Or deep-fry?

805
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:35,940
-She's steaming it.
-Steaming.

806
00:29:36,007 --> 00:29:39,010
-And she adds… cooking wine.
-A bit of cooking wine.

807
00:29:39,077 --> 00:29:40,979
She uses cooking wine
to remove the fishy odor.

808
00:29:41,045 --> 00:29:42,180
SLAM

809
00:29:42,247 --> 00:29:44,916
-She slams loudly.
-Spanking the green onion.

810
00:29:44,983 --> 00:29:46,785
Spanking the green onion?

811
00:29:46,851 --> 00:29:49,420
She's adding some green onion flavor.

812
00:29:51,089 --> 00:29:53,525
Jong-won begins by slicing a cucumber.

813
00:29:53,591 --> 00:29:56,094
-He salts it lightly.
-Yes.

814
00:29:56,661 --> 00:29:57,695
Slicing an onion?

815
00:29:57,762 --> 00:29:58,930
An onion.

816
00:29:59,697 --> 00:30:01,232
PUT IN ICED WATER TO MELLOW THEM OUT

817
00:30:01,299 --> 00:30:03,401
Chef Jong-won grinds shrimp.

818
00:30:04,269 --> 00:30:07,338
-I think he's making shrimp balls.
-Shrimp balls.

819
00:30:07,405 --> 00:30:10,408
-Jong-won grabs a piping bag.
-A piping bag.

820
00:30:11,276 --> 00:30:12,410
-Shrimps.
-Shrimp balls.

821
00:30:12,477 --> 00:30:13,745
Is he going to squeeze them out?

822
00:30:13,812 --> 00:30:15,046
ONE HAND SPINS THE BAG

823
00:30:15,446 --> 00:30:16,314
THE OTHER COOKS NOODLES!

824
00:30:16,381 --> 00:30:18,550
-He's cooking noodles.
-Noodles, right?

825
00:30:18,616 --> 00:30:19,450
SETS THE TIMER

826
00:30:20,051 --> 00:30:22,086
SHRIMP MIXTURE IN THE PIPING BAG

827
00:30:22,153 --> 00:30:24,122
I'm filling <i>dureup</i> with this.

828
00:30:24,189 --> 00:30:26,391
He'll fill it between the leaves.

829
00:30:26,457 --> 00:30:28,259
Yes, and he said he'd deep-fry those.

830
00:30:28,326 --> 00:30:31,663
There's a traditional type of <i>jeon</i>
made with <i>dureup</i> and shrimp.

831
00:30:31,729 --> 00:30:32,964
-That sounds good.
-I see.

832
00:30:33,031 --> 00:30:35,400
It's my modernized take on it.

833
00:30:36,034 --> 00:30:36,868
I'M USING DUREUP TOO!

834
00:30:36,935 --> 00:30:39,337
-<i>Dureup</i>.
-<i>Dureup</i>, <i>dureup</i>, <i>dureup</i>.

835
00:30:39,404 --> 00:30:40,271
-<i>Dureup</i>.
-<i>Dureup</i>.

836
00:30:40,338 --> 00:30:42,974
-The <i>dureup</i> looks so fresh.
-Yes.

837
00:30:43,041 --> 00:30:46,277
Both chefs are using <i>dureup</i>!

838
00:30:46,344 --> 00:30:48,346
Doesn't it seem like
they're using different <i>dureup</i>?

839
00:30:48,413 --> 00:30:50,014
-They're different.
-They are.

840
00:30:50,081 --> 00:30:52,250
They're different kinds,
tree-<i>dureup</i> and ground-<i>dureup</i>.

841
00:30:52,317 --> 00:30:53,751
-I see.
-I'm using

842
00:30:53,818 --> 00:30:56,788
Aralia elata, tree-<i>dureup </i>grown on a tree.

843
00:30:56,855 --> 00:30:58,189
I'm using Aralia cordata, ground-<i>dureup.</i>

844
00:30:58,256 --> 00:31:01,893
-<i>Dureup </i>grows on the tip of the branches.
-Off the branch?

845
00:31:01,960 --> 00:31:04,028
<i>-Chef Jong-won is using tree-</i>dureup<i>.</i>
<i>-Tree-</i>dureup<i>.</i>

846
00:31:04,095 --> 00:31:07,532
Right now, shoots that grow on trees
are in season right now,

847
00:31:07,599 --> 00:31:08,900
so my <i>dureup </i>is more delicious.

848
00:31:10,401 --> 00:31:11,502
IS THAT SO?

849
00:31:11,803 --> 00:31:12,871
OH, GOSH…

850
00:31:12,937 --> 00:31:14,539
Ones grown on trees are the real deal.

851
00:31:14,606 --> 00:31:16,040
TREE-DUREUP IS THE AUTHENTIC DUREUP!

852
00:31:16,107 --> 00:31:17,609
She didn't have a better understanding.

853
00:31:18,576 --> 00:31:21,346
Jong-won found a second
to promote his dish.

854
00:31:21,412 --> 00:31:23,314
His talk improved a lot.

855
00:31:23,381 --> 00:31:25,650
-Don't you think so?
-Unbelievable.

856
00:31:25,717 --> 00:31:28,586
I wonder how much he will have changed
by the end of the year.

857
00:31:28,653 --> 00:31:31,723
MEASURING THE EXACT AMOUNT OF COLD BEER!

858
00:31:31,789 --> 00:31:33,491
He's using beer.

859
00:31:33,558 --> 00:31:35,126
-And frying powder.
-Frying powder and beer.

860
00:31:35,193 --> 00:31:37,128
It adds more air to the batter.

861
00:31:37,195 --> 00:31:38,730
And makes it crispier?

862
00:31:38,796 --> 00:31:40,498
When you deep-fry, keep the batter cold,

863
00:31:40,565 --> 00:31:41,699
gluten low,

864
00:31:41,766 --> 00:31:43,835
and the carbonation high
to make the fritters crispy.

865
00:31:43,902 --> 00:31:45,670
I'm using cold beer
for all three purposes.

866
00:31:45,737 --> 00:31:47,572
-You can use sparkling water, right?
-Yes.

867
00:31:47,639 --> 00:31:49,173
I'm learning a lot today.

868
00:31:49,240 --> 00:31:50,308
3. FILL DUREUP WITH SHRIMP

869
00:31:50,375 --> 00:31:51,542
He's filling it.

870
00:31:51,609 --> 00:31:53,044
Between the stems.

871
00:31:53,111 --> 00:31:54,846
-Then it'll be deep-fried, right?
-Looks good.

872
00:31:55,446 --> 00:31:56,514
DEEP-FRIED, YOU SAY?

873
00:31:56,581 --> 00:31:59,584
He adds the shrimp mixture
between the stems.

874
00:31:59,651 --> 00:32:00,585
That's new.

875
00:32:02,120 --> 00:32:03,288
SPRINKLE FRYING BATTER ON TOP

876
00:32:03,354 --> 00:32:05,657
What's he doing?
He sprinkled frying batter on top.

877
00:32:05,723 --> 00:32:08,192
-I've covered it lightly.
-Lightly covered.

878
00:32:08,259 --> 00:32:10,762
-Lightly.
-I'll keep these cold.

879
00:32:10,828 --> 00:32:12,096
You have 12 minutes left.

880
00:32:12,730 --> 00:32:14,365
CHOPPING CHIVES

881
00:32:14,432 --> 00:32:16,768
What's Chef Eun-yeong making?

882
00:32:16,834 --> 00:32:19,003
-I'm making chive sauce.
-Chive sauce?

883
00:32:19,070 --> 00:32:21,005
Yes, chives are in season too.

884
00:32:21,072 --> 00:32:23,041
-Gochujang and <i>yuja cheong</i>.
-Yes.

885
00:32:23,107 --> 00:32:24,676
-Vinegar.
-Gochujang?

886
00:32:24,742 --> 00:32:26,711
-That's dangerous.
-Why?

887
00:32:26,778 --> 00:32:27,979
She mixed gochujang and <i>yuja cheong</i>.

888
00:32:28,046 --> 00:32:29,247
LOST WITH THIS COMBO LAST TIME

889
00:32:29,314 --> 00:32:31,683
So I'm adding some perilla oil

890
00:32:31,749 --> 00:32:33,184
to capture that old dude's appetite.

891
00:32:33,685 --> 00:32:34,552
PERILLA OIL

892
00:32:34,619 --> 00:32:37,255
Chef Eun-yeong keeps saying
she has an old dude's appetite,

893
00:32:37,322 --> 00:32:38,423
but I'm an old dude myself.

894
00:32:39,691 --> 00:32:41,526
ANOTHER COUNTER PUNCH!

895
00:32:41,592 --> 00:32:42,927
-He's actually an old dude.
-He's an old dude.

896
00:32:42,994 --> 00:32:44,228
-Jong-won…
-If you look closely,

897
00:32:44,295 --> 00:32:46,331
I have hair on my chin.
I'm an actual old dude.

898
00:32:46,397 --> 00:32:48,499
I have hair on my chin.
I'm an actual old dude.

899
00:32:49,167 --> 00:32:50,234
HE CAN'T EVEN REFUTE THAT…

900
00:32:50,301 --> 00:32:51,703
THE OLD DUDES ARE IN AWE

901
00:32:52,270 --> 00:32:55,139
THE LUNATIC IS ON ANOTHER LEVEL

902
00:32:55,206 --> 00:32:58,042
-What kind of talk is this? What the heck?
-"Ahem."

903
00:32:58,109 --> 00:33:00,011
LOST THE WILL TO FIGHT

904
00:33:00,078 --> 00:33:01,479
-Hey! Darn it.
-It's true.

905
00:33:02,647 --> 00:33:04,115
At the very least, you need to make sense.

906
00:33:04,549 --> 00:33:06,317
Did you shave this morning?

907
00:33:06,384 --> 00:33:07,452
I did this morning.

908
00:33:07,518 --> 00:33:09,287
It's the evening,
so it has grown out a bit.

909
00:33:09,354 --> 00:33:11,389
THE BRIDE-TO-BE'S DIGNITY

910
00:33:11,456 --> 00:33:13,491
-I'll recommend a nice razor.
-Thanks.

911
00:33:14,058 --> 00:33:15,093
CAN'T COPY THIS KIND OF LUNACY

912
00:33:15,159 --> 00:33:16,194
She really wants to win.

913
00:33:16,260 --> 00:33:17,795
She's been getting lots of ad offers,

914
00:33:17,862 --> 00:33:21,332
and she might become the first female chef
to do an ad for a razor.

915
00:33:21,399 --> 00:33:23,968
-The Manila clam broth.
-That broth.

916
00:33:24,035 --> 00:33:26,337
They're scaring me today.

917
00:33:26,404 --> 00:33:29,107
I can almost hear
the sound of their swords clashing.

918
00:33:29,173 --> 00:33:31,376
The two born fighters have met.

919
00:33:31,442 --> 00:33:34,479
Winning this cook-off will mean
much more than just one victory.

920
00:33:34,545 --> 00:33:35,446
BEEP

921
00:33:35,513 --> 00:33:37,482
COOKED THE NOODLES FOR EXACTLY 3 MINUTES

922
00:33:37,915 --> 00:33:39,384
COOL IN ICED WATER

923
00:33:39,450 --> 00:33:40,718
Noodles.

924
00:33:41,285 --> 00:33:44,322
BOILING SOY-BASED SAUCE, OUT

925
00:33:44,389 --> 00:33:47,692
I'm using wild chives
to make wild chive soy sauce.

926
00:33:47,759 --> 00:33:49,127
FILLED WITH THE SCENT OF SPRING

927
00:33:49,193 --> 00:33:51,062
-Wild chives.
-Wild chive soy sauce.

928
00:33:51,129 --> 00:33:52,864
It's tough to beat that sauce.

929
00:33:52,930 --> 00:33:56,000
-Wild chive soy sauce.
-All you need is that and white rice.

930
00:33:56,067 --> 00:33:58,036
Can you make a lot?
I want to take some home.

931
00:33:58,870 --> 00:34:00,138
He's adding more.

932
00:34:00,204 --> 00:34:03,274
-Mix that with rice, and it's game over.
-It already tastes good.

933
00:34:03,341 --> 00:34:05,176
He wants you to make a lot
to take some home.

934
00:34:05,243 --> 00:34:07,011
THE OLD DUDE SERIOUSLY WANTS THE SAUCE

935
00:34:07,578 --> 00:34:09,547
EUN-YEONG WON'T BACK DOWN
AND ALSO USES SOY SAUCE!

936
00:34:10,148 --> 00:34:11,416
It's going straight inside.

937
00:34:11,482 --> 00:34:13,351
-Soy sauce.
-For the fritter? Is that soy sauce?

938
00:34:13,418 --> 00:34:15,720
She mixed soy sauce and ground pepper
into Manila clam broth.

939
00:34:15,787 --> 00:34:18,156
-She mixed soy sauce into the broth?
-Yes.

940
00:34:18,222 --> 00:34:21,192
I'll top the fish later with this sauce.

941
00:34:21,259 --> 00:34:23,327
-Soy sauce.
-It's a battle of soy sauces.

942
00:34:23,394 --> 00:34:25,163
Soy sauce has to become the key.

943
00:34:25,229 --> 00:34:26,063
What about oyster sauce?

944
00:34:26,130 --> 00:34:28,132
-Yes, I need to add that.
-Oyster sauce.

945
00:34:28,199 --> 00:34:29,634
She forgot oyster sauce.

946
00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:31,269
I saved your dish.

947
00:34:31,836 --> 00:34:32,904
GOOD ONE

948
00:34:32,970 --> 00:34:33,838
Nice job.

949
00:34:33,905 --> 00:34:35,606
-The young guns help each other out.
-Of course.

950
00:34:35,673 --> 00:34:37,442
-Trust me.
-They bicker yet have a bond.

951
00:34:37,508 --> 00:34:38,676
HIGHLY DOUBT THAT…

952
00:34:39,010 --> 00:34:40,144
WHAT'S JONG-WON UP TO?

953
00:34:41,145 --> 00:34:42,580
He's dropping <i>dureup</i> in.

954
00:34:42,647 --> 00:34:43,481
DUREUP GOES IN

955
00:34:43,781 --> 00:34:46,050
This time, he soaks them in the batter.

956
00:34:46,117 --> 00:34:48,553
-If you think about it…
-<i>Dureup </i>fritter.

957
00:34:48,619 --> 00:34:50,288
That looks so good.

958
00:34:50,354 --> 00:34:51,189
