1200
00:43:13,524 --> 00:43:14,792
THE DISH IS IMPECCABLE

1201
00:43:14,858 --> 00:43:16,727
He has to try it.

1202
00:43:17,294 --> 00:43:18,429
What shall I eat next?

1203
00:43:18,495 --> 00:43:21,098
-Next, <i>ganghoe</i>.
-<i>Ganghoe</i>.

1204
00:43:21,165 --> 00:43:23,534
It's slightly boiled seafood
wrapped in veggies.

1205
00:43:23,601 --> 00:43:26,637
-It's cuttlefish with shepherd's purse.
-Shepherd's purse.

1206
00:43:26,704 --> 00:43:28,272
-Did you wrap it with wild chives?
-Yes.

1207
00:43:28,339 --> 00:43:30,441
-It's also a spring green.
-Wild chives are also in season.

1208
00:43:31,375 --> 00:43:32,910
That's really has to be so tasty.

1209
00:43:34,311 --> 00:43:36,847
CRUNCH

1210
00:43:36,914 --> 00:43:38,382
I can hear the crunches.

1211
00:43:38,949 --> 00:43:41,018
He's a general, so he has strong jaws.

1212
00:43:41,085 --> 00:43:42,152
Nice jaws.

1213
00:43:42,219 --> 00:43:43,187
GENERAL-ESQUE JAWS

1214
00:43:43,487 --> 00:43:44,355
The cuttlefish

1215
00:43:44,922 --> 00:43:45,990
is cooked perfectly.

1216
00:43:47,024 --> 00:43:50,794
Also, wild chives, shepherd's purse,
and <i>chogochujang</i> go together very well.

1217
00:43:50,861 --> 00:43:52,863
-Does it go well with soju?
-Yes, it's excellent.

1218
00:43:52,930 --> 00:43:54,131
A PERFECT BAR SNACK TOO

1219
00:43:54,198 --> 00:43:56,867
Also, there is this ancient saying,

1220
00:43:56,934 --> 00:43:58,535
"Drink first, noodles later."

1221
00:43:58,602 --> 00:44:00,237
-"Drink first, noodles later"?
-Yes.

1222
00:44:00,304 --> 00:44:02,172
-First, drink.
-Yes.

1223
00:44:02,239 --> 00:44:03,474
And then the noodles.

1224
00:44:03,540 --> 00:44:04,608
I didn't know that saying.

1225
00:44:04,675 --> 00:44:05,909
KOREAN DICTIONARY
DRINK FIRST, THEN NOODLES

1226
00:44:05,976 --> 00:44:08,712
-The third dish, the noodles.
-Webfoot octopus.

1227
00:44:09,446 --> 00:44:11,715
A noodle dish
made with wild chives and webfoot octopus.

1228
00:44:11,782 --> 00:44:14,718
Just as he's about to eat, what if
someone shouts, "The enemies are here"?

1229
00:44:15,452 --> 00:44:16,854
Tell them to wait.

1230
00:44:17,888 --> 00:44:18,822
NOODLES FIRST, FIGHT LATER

1231
00:44:18,889 --> 00:44:21,058
Are they Japanese? <i>Chotto matte.</i>

1232
00:44:21,125 --> 00:44:22,760
If Chinese, <i>deng yi xia.</i>

1233
00:44:23,861 --> 00:44:25,396
-He'll have one bite.
-"<i>Deng yi xia</i>"?

1234
00:44:26,463 --> 00:44:27,798
BEGINS TO SLURP THE NOODLES

1235
00:44:27,865 --> 00:44:30,501
He seasoned it with soy-based sauce.

1236
00:44:30,567 --> 00:44:32,169
That soy sauce was excellent.

1237
00:44:32,236 --> 00:44:34,938
I see something else in here.
What's this green thing?

1238
00:44:35,005 --> 00:44:36,407
I added webfoot octopus,

1239
00:44:36,473 --> 00:44:39,043
and you said you liked cilantro,
so I chopped some in the sauce.

1240
00:44:39,109 --> 00:44:40,811
<i>-Cilantro.</i>
<i>-A bit of cilantro.</i>

1241
00:44:44,348 --> 00:44:45,215
Mmm!

1242
00:44:46,216 --> 00:44:47,751
-I can taste it.
-The cilantro?

1243
00:44:47,818 --> 00:44:48,952
-Yes.
-I see.

1244
00:44:49,019 --> 00:44:50,354
I can feel <i>gosu </i>nearby.

1245
00:44:50,421 --> 00:44:51,822
HE'S ACTUALLY NEARBY

1246
00:44:51,889 --> 00:44:54,425
-Go Soo is here.
-He's in front of you and in the dish.

1247
00:44:54,491 --> 00:44:57,695
Go Soo is looking at me,
and I'm feeling <i>gosu</i>.

1248
00:44:57,761 --> 00:44:59,963
-You're right. Double Go Soo.
-Double Go Soo.

1249
00:45:00,030 --> 00:45:01,165
Double Go Soo.

1250
00:45:01,231 --> 00:45:02,366
Eating <i>gosu </i>before Go Soo?

1251
00:45:02,433 --> 00:45:03,600
-Yes.
-That's so rare.

1252
00:45:03,667 --> 00:45:07,137
-It's rare to eat <i>gosu</i> before Go Soo.
-It's a rare opportunity.

1253
00:45:07,204 --> 00:45:08,839
Why do I…

1254
00:45:08,906 --> 00:45:10,140
keep flinching?

1255
00:45:10,207 --> 00:45:11,375
I feel like I'm being eaten.

1256
00:45:12,443 --> 00:45:14,078
Are you flinching?

1257
00:45:14,144 --> 00:45:17,114
Next, the last bit of soju.

1258
00:45:17,748 --> 00:45:18,982
That's it.

1259
00:45:19,049 --> 00:45:20,050
A nice finish.

1260
00:45:20,117 --> 00:45:22,152
-Remove it.
-Yes, sir.

1261
00:45:22,720 --> 00:45:23,887
BACKING OUT FRIVOLOUSLY

1262
00:45:23,954 --> 00:45:26,090
Next, Chef Eun-yeong's dish,

1263
00:45:26,423 --> 00:45:28,225
CHIVE SAUCE, YUJA CHOGOCHUJANG

1264
00:45:28,292 --> 00:45:30,027
CLEAN WEBFOOT OCTOPUS SOUP

1265
00:45:30,094 --> 00:45:32,863
AND STEAMED FLOUNDER
TOPPED WITH SPRING GREENS

1266
00:45:33,564 --> 00:45:36,133
DUREUP WILL BLOOM SPRING IN HIS MOUTH

1267
00:45:36,500 --> 00:45:40,404
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
FLOUNDER, DUREUP, DUREUP, DUREUP

1268
00:45:40,471 --> 00:45:43,040
The dish is being kept warm

1269
00:45:43,107 --> 00:45:45,442
-with a warmer below.
-Yes.

1270
00:45:45,509 --> 00:45:48,011
First of all,
I wanted to give you the whole fish,

1271
00:45:48,078 --> 00:45:50,781
but there was an accident,
so I mostly saved the tail part.

1272
00:45:50,848 --> 00:45:53,984
Actually, fish tails are the best part.

1273
00:45:54,051 --> 00:45:55,853
-It's the head.
-Isn't it the head?

1274
00:45:55,919 --> 00:45:58,422
During times of famine,
people didn't want to eat the head,

1275
00:45:58,489 --> 00:46:00,991
so they probably said that
to make other people eat it.

1276
00:46:01,058 --> 00:46:02,326
People probably made it up.

1277
00:46:02,392 --> 00:46:04,495
-Probably?
-I think the tail is more delicious.

1278
00:46:04,561 --> 00:46:06,230
That's your personal take, right?

1279
00:46:06,296 --> 00:46:08,365
Enjoy the fish with the soy sauce

1280
00:46:08,432 --> 00:46:11,869
and try the <i>dureup </i>with <i>chogochujang</i>.

1281
00:46:12,436 --> 00:46:14,772
-All right.
-As for the soup on the side,

1282
00:46:14,838 --> 00:46:16,640
you'll see the chive sauce I made.

1283
00:46:16,707 --> 00:46:18,442
Try it with a bit of sauce on top.

1284
00:46:18,509 --> 00:46:20,477
-Chive sauce on the soup.
-Yes.

1285
00:46:20,544 --> 00:46:23,113
STEAMING

1286
00:46:24,181 --> 00:46:26,283
-It's hot.
-Give it here.

1287
00:46:26,350 --> 00:46:27,384
Wait, it's hot.

1288
00:46:27,451 --> 00:46:29,853
It's really hot. How did you stay so calm?

1289
00:46:29,920 --> 00:46:31,421
This is why he's a general.

1290
00:46:31,488 --> 00:46:33,657
He does not feel that it's hot.

1291
00:46:35,359 --> 00:46:36,426
All right.

1292
00:46:36,493 --> 00:46:37,761
The flounder.

1293
00:46:37,828 --> 00:46:38,929
SHE MANAGED TO SAVE A LOT

1294
00:46:38,996 --> 00:46:42,399
-She saved quite a lot.
-There's some meat.

1295
00:46:42,466 --> 00:46:44,935
She's a Chinese chef,

1296
00:46:45,002 --> 00:46:49,640
so I expected her to deep-fry ingredients
and make dishes with a strong flavor.

1297
00:46:49,706 --> 00:46:51,742
I didn't expect a steamed dish.

1298
00:46:52,776 --> 00:46:54,244
All right.

1299
00:46:54,311 --> 00:46:55,579
Flounder in season.

1300
00:46:55,646 --> 00:46:57,080
WILL IT TASTE AMAZING TOO?

1301
00:46:57,748 --> 00:46:59,783
-Whoa.
-Whoa?

1302
00:46:59,850 --> 00:47:01,952
-Can I eat the fish roe too?
-Of course, you can.

1303
00:47:06,123 --> 00:47:07,257
What's it like?

1304
00:47:07,324 --> 00:47:09,293
There's a lot of flavor

1305
00:47:09,359 --> 00:47:10,661
in this soy sauce.

1306
00:47:10,727 --> 00:47:12,162
DEEP, RICH FLAVOR

1307
00:47:12,229 --> 00:47:15,899
-Did you make it with Manila clams?
-Yes, with Manila clam broth.

1308
00:47:15,966 --> 00:47:18,135
She made it with Manila clam broth.

1309
00:47:18,202 --> 00:47:19,469
THE AMAZEMENT DEEPENS

1310
00:47:19,536 --> 00:47:22,139
-Next, try some <i>dureup </i>with <i>chogochujang</i>.
-<i>Dureup </i>and <i>chogochujang</i>.

1311
00:47:22,206 --> 00:47:25,242
-It's named <i>dureup</i>, so it must be the key.
-Yes.

1312
00:47:25,309 --> 00:47:27,377
-It's in season right now.
-Ground-<i>dureup</i>.

1313
00:47:28,345 --> 00:47:30,881
EATS A WHOLE DUREUP

1314
00:47:30,948 --> 00:47:32,282
It must be tender.

1315
00:47:33,350 --> 00:47:35,652
CURIOUS

1316
00:47:35,719 --> 00:47:37,855
-It's a spring green, right?
-Yes.

1317
00:47:37,921 --> 00:47:38,889
Does it feel like spring?

1318
00:47:38,956 --> 00:47:42,059
It's an explosion of spring.

1319
00:47:43,060 --> 00:47:45,095
THAT'S WHY DUREUP IS IN THE NAME

1320
00:47:45,162 --> 00:47:46,096
It's not just spring.

1321
00:47:46,697 --> 00:47:48,298
It's spurting.

1322
00:47:48,365 --> 00:47:50,434
-Spurting.
-Spring is spurting.

1323
00:47:50,500 --> 00:47:53,170
-Spring is spurting.
-That's what's happening.

1324
00:47:53,237 --> 00:47:56,139
Spring is spurting.
That's why seasonal dishes are great.

1325
00:47:56,707 --> 00:47:58,976
-Some webfoot octopus.
-It was cooked perfectly.

1326
00:47:59,543 --> 00:48:00,744
And some sauce.

1327
00:48:00,811 --> 00:48:03,080
-Just like that.
-That's it.

1328
00:48:03,146 --> 00:48:04,648
Chinese-style soup.

1329
00:48:06,350 --> 00:48:07,918
-What's it like?
-The webfoot octopus.

1330
00:48:07,985 --> 00:48:10,754
-It must be firm and juicy.
-Firm and juicy.

1331
00:48:12,055 --> 00:48:13,557
Gosh, this is…

1332
00:48:14,124 --> 00:48:17,160
IS HE AMAZED OR DISAPPOINTED?

1333
00:48:17,227 --> 00:48:18,829
This is really good.

1334
00:48:18,896 --> 00:48:20,797
Is it really good?

1335
00:48:20,864 --> 00:48:25,335
-That was genuine.
-This chive sauce tastes really rich.

1336
00:48:25,402 --> 00:48:27,304
It webs well with webfoot octopus.

1337
00:48:27,371 --> 00:48:28,839
THE OLD DUDE LOVES THE DAD JOKE

1338
00:48:28,906 --> 00:48:30,274
The chive sauce.

1339
00:48:30,340 --> 00:48:32,209
I was surprised.

1340
00:48:32,276 --> 00:48:35,012
-I usually dip it in the red sauce.
-Right.

1341
00:48:35,679 --> 00:48:37,281
He also tries it without the sauce.

1342
00:48:38,348 --> 00:48:40,217
Wow, this…

1343
00:48:40,284 --> 00:48:41,218
This soup is so nice.

1344
00:48:41,785 --> 00:48:44,221
THE SOUP TOTALLY CAPTIVATES HIS PALATE!

1345
00:48:44,288 --> 00:48:46,390
Everyone who loves to drink loves soup.

1346
00:48:46,456 --> 00:48:47,925
The umami

1347
00:48:47,991 --> 00:48:49,326
spurts.

1348
00:48:49,393 --> 00:48:51,862
The umami spurts. It exploded.

1349
00:48:52,429 --> 00:48:53,964
ADJUSTS HIS GRIP ON THE SPOON

1350
00:48:54,031 --> 00:48:57,167
When people who love to drink
hold the spoon like that, it's over.

1351
00:48:57,234 --> 00:48:58,936
Once he grabs it like this,

1352
00:48:59,002 --> 00:49:01,104
it means he's wondering,
"Should I get wasted or not?"

1353
00:49:01,171 --> 00:49:04,508
-Absolutely right.
-Yes, he's wondering if he should go hard.

1354
00:49:04,574 --> 00:49:07,210
He can't keep himself
from staring at the drink.

1355
00:49:07,277 --> 00:49:10,981
It was served with his dish,
so I couldn't just grab it.

1356
00:49:11,048 --> 00:49:13,550
-It's only for that dish.
-Yes, it's only for that one.

1357
00:49:13,617 --> 00:49:16,019
This one has a deep flavor too,

1358
00:49:16,086 --> 00:49:17,587
but this one is just…

1359
00:49:17,654 --> 00:49:18,655
THE KICK IS
THE WEBFOOT OCTOPUS SOUP

1360
00:49:18,722 --> 00:49:20,090
-The soup is that good?
-Yes.

1361
00:49:20,157 --> 00:49:23,927
He tasted a deep flavor,
an even deeper flavor from the soup.

1362
00:49:23,994 --> 00:49:24,928
AH

1363
00:49:25,495 --> 00:49:27,264
I know what that feels like.

1364
00:49:27,331 --> 00:49:28,865
CAN IMAGINE HOW GOOD IT IS

1365
00:49:28,932 --> 00:49:32,169
It's such a familiar taste,

1366
00:49:32,235 --> 00:49:34,171
but it's much classier.

1367
00:49:34,738 --> 00:49:35,639
CLEAR SOUP MEETS SEASONAL SEAFOOD

1368
00:49:35,706 --> 00:49:37,207
-Familiar yet classy.
-Yes.

1369
00:49:38,041 --> 00:49:40,143
But that one felt like

1370
00:49:40,210 --> 00:49:43,246
<i>I was treated to a nice, luxurious meal.</i>

1371
00:49:43,814 --> 00:49:46,917
NECK-AND-NECK

1372
00:49:46,984 --> 00:49:50,654
Now, why don't we let Soo have a bite?

1373
00:49:50,721 --> 00:49:53,623
-It's still crispy even now.
-I can hear the crunch all the way here.

1374
00:49:53,690 --> 00:49:55,993
-And he loves fritters.
-He does.

1375
00:49:56,059 --> 00:49:57,928
YES, I DO LOVE FRITTERS

1376
00:49:59,896 --> 00:50:00,897
The fritter

1377
00:50:00,964 --> 00:50:03,200
just melted in my mouth.

1378
00:50:03,266 --> 00:50:04,801
It disintegrates softly

1379
00:50:04,868 --> 00:50:05,869
and melts in the mouth.

1380
00:50:05,936 --> 00:50:08,638
And the dredge wasn't too thick.

1381
00:50:08,705 --> 00:50:11,208
Cuttlefish with seasonal greens.

1382
00:50:12,876 --> 00:50:15,579
-Bell peppers go so well with this.
-With cuttlefish?

1383
00:50:15,645 --> 00:50:16,713
It's nice, isn't it?

1384
00:50:16,780 --> 00:50:20,484
It tastes different
when everything is tied together.

1385
00:50:21,685 --> 00:50:23,987
Lastly, the noodles.

1386
00:50:24,054 --> 00:50:25,722
He also loves noodles.

1387
00:50:25,789 --> 00:50:28,358
He loved his noodle dishes,
and it's yet another noodle dish.

1388
00:50:29,092 --> 00:50:30,794
He's trying this one.

1389
00:50:30,861 --> 00:50:32,696
We're seeing Go Soo eating <i>gosu</i>.

1390
00:50:32,763 --> 00:50:35,999
-We're witnessing a rare sight.
-You're right.

1391
00:50:36,066 --> 00:50:38,568
Is there video footage
of Go Soo eating <i>gosu?</i>

1392
00:50:38,635 --> 00:50:42,039
-There is now.
-There is now, right? We called dibs.

1393
00:50:42,105 --> 00:50:45,142
-Go Soo eats <i>gosu</i>.
-A shot of Go Soo eating <i>gosu</i>.

1394
00:50:46,743 --> 00:50:48,345
-It's so good.
-Is it?

1395
00:50:49,279 --> 00:50:52,749
The webfoot octopus is firm and juicy,

1396
00:50:52,816 --> 00:50:56,119
and the mix of wild chives and cilantro

1397
00:50:56,186 --> 00:50:58,321
adds lots of flavor.

1398
00:50:58,388 --> 00:51:00,624
Next, Chef Eun-yeong's dish.

1399
00:51:00,690 --> 00:51:04,194
-Flounder, <i>Dureup, Dureup, Dureup.</i>
-Seasonal food is good for you too.

1400
00:51:04,261 --> 00:51:06,863
You're right.
And that must bring out a nice texture.

1401
00:51:10,400 --> 00:51:12,269
IS SPRING SPURTING?

1402
00:51:12,836 --> 00:51:14,404
That's so refreshing.

1403
00:51:14,471 --> 00:51:15,639
-Is it really?
-Is it? It feels refreshing.

1404
00:51:15,705 --> 00:51:17,607
THE WHOLE MOUTH IS REFRESHED BY THE DUREUP

1405
00:51:18,108 --> 00:51:20,444
Are flounder and <i>dureup</i>

1406
00:51:20,510 --> 00:51:21,978
highly compatible?

1407
00:51:23,346 --> 00:51:24,448
Was that a question?

1408
00:51:25,115 --> 00:51:28,018
-Are you asking me? Ask the chef.
-I'm sure she made it because it is.

1409
00:51:28,085 --> 00:51:29,686
IF YOU'RE CURIOUS, YOU OWE US 500 WON

1410
00:51:29,753 --> 00:51:33,490
Steamed fish in Chinese cuisine
usually finishes with a cilantro topping,

1411
00:51:33,557 --> 00:51:36,359
but I wanted to add the flavor of spring

1412
00:51:36,426 --> 00:51:38,361
by using <i>dureup</i> instead of cilantro.

1413
00:51:38,428 --> 00:51:40,730
Herbs go very well with steamed fish.

1414
00:51:40,797 --> 00:51:43,600
The scent of <i>dureup </i>is very strong.

1415
00:51:43,667 --> 00:51:45,335
-It smells strong.
-Try the soup.

1416
00:51:45,402 --> 00:51:48,572
Jong-hyuk loved this webfoot octopus soup.

1417
00:51:48,638 --> 00:51:51,842
-He was surprised by the chive sauce.
-And the soup.

1418
00:51:51,908 --> 00:51:53,510
I wonder if he'll react the same.

1419
00:51:54,077 --> 00:51:57,447
The smell of chives hits me hard.

1420
00:51:57,514 --> 00:51:59,049
It's delicious.

1421
00:51:59,116 --> 00:52:00,684
-Aren't the ingredients nice?
-Yes.

1422
00:52:01,318 --> 00:52:03,753
And now, it's time to choose.

1423
00:52:03,820 --> 00:52:06,490
<i>Press one to pick Son Jong-won,</i>

1424
00:52:06,556 --> 00:52:07,991
<i>and two to pick Park Eun-yeong.</i>

1425
00:52:08,925 --> 00:52:12,429
Make your decision and press the button.

1426
00:52:12,496 --> 00:52:14,364
-I did.
-He made his decision quickly.

1427
00:52:14,431 --> 00:52:17,300
Let's find out who he chose!

1428
00:52:17,367 --> 00:52:18,802
Show us!

1429
00:52:18,869 --> 00:52:20,137
Season's Dignity.

1430
00:52:20,203 --> 00:52:24,541
Will Chef Jong-won successfully get
his revenge against Eun-yeong?

1431
00:52:24,608 --> 00:52:28,512
Or will Chef Eun-yeong throw
another wet blanket over him?

1432
00:52:28,578 --> 00:52:30,347
Who did Jong-hyuk choose?

1433
00:52:30,413 --> 00:52:31,882
Which one is it?

1434
00:52:31,948 --> 00:52:33,717
Season's Dignity!

1435
00:52:33,783 --> 00:52:34,851
Season's Dignity!

1436
00:52:36,553 --> 00:52:37,454
Who'll take the star?

1437
00:52:37,521 --> 00:52:38,822
SON JONG-WON WINS

1438
00:52:39,189 --> 00:52:40,390
I MUST WANT TO BE DRUNK
ON SPRING TODAY WINS

1439
00:52:40,457 --> 00:52:41,725
Jong-won wins.

1440
00:52:42,325 --> 00:52:44,094
Jong-won takes the victory.

1441
00:52:44,161 --> 00:52:45,395
He beat the soup.

1442
00:52:45,462 --> 00:52:46,997
Fish heads are better than tails.

1443
00:52:47,063 --> 00:52:49,666
Chef Jong-won's <i>dureup</i> fritter

1444
00:52:49,733 --> 00:52:52,536
was way too delicious.

1445
00:52:52,602 --> 00:52:56,173
<i>It had all different textures.</i>
<i>The dredge, the dureup, and the shrimp.</i>

1446
00:52:56,239 --> 00:52:58,708
<i>It felt like I was eating something</i>
<i>very luxurious.</i>

1447
00:52:58,775 --> 00:53:01,311
<i>I also loved the presentation</i>
<i>with the table he used.</i>

1448
00:53:01,378 --> 00:53:04,948
It almost got me thinking that
I went back in time to the Joseon era.

1449
00:53:05,015 --> 00:53:09,386
I felt like I was sitting
in front of a waterfall,

1450
00:53:09,452 --> 00:53:11,588
about to write poetry.

1451
00:53:11,655 --> 00:53:12,689
Wearing an overcoat.

1452
00:53:12,756 --> 00:53:14,691
It's a bit of a shame, Chef Eun-yeong.

1453
00:53:14,758 --> 00:53:16,293
When the flounder fell to the floor,

1454
00:53:16,359 --> 00:53:18,361
it felt like my guts also fell out.

1455
00:53:19,529 --> 00:53:22,032
-Your guts?
-You're going that far?

1456
00:53:22,098 --> 00:53:25,936
I'm happy that
I got to serve both dishes for Jong-hyuk.

1457
00:53:26,002 --> 00:53:27,137
It's a relief.

1458
00:53:27,204 --> 00:53:28,538
It looks like your beard has grown.

1459
00:53:28,605 --> 00:53:31,808
-I have to go and shave it off.
-You should go right now.

1460
00:53:32,375 --> 00:53:34,477
DOES SHE HAVE TO TRY THIS HARD?

1461
00:53:34,544 --> 00:53:37,180
This means Chef Jong-won gets
his seventh victory.

1462
00:53:37,247 --> 00:53:39,683
He's securing his spot at the top.

1463
00:53:39,749 --> 00:53:41,718
Who's going to stop Jong-won?

1464
00:53:41,785 --> 00:53:44,321
Please put a star on him!

1465
00:53:44,821 --> 00:53:47,224
He continues to secure his place
as the sole first place!

1466
00:53:47,958 --> 00:53:50,126
Jong-won's seventh win!

1467
00:53:50,193 --> 00:53:51,261
Congratulations!

1468
00:53:54,798 --> 00:53:59,035
<i>The second round of cook-off</i>
<i>with Jong-hyuk's ingredients.</i>

1469
00:53:59,102 --> 00:54:01,438
The man who knows
every known hangover cure for mankind,

1470
00:54:01,504 --> 00:54:04,274
the big drinker of the show,
Chef Jung Ho-young.

1471
00:54:04,341 --> 00:54:05,242
Whoa.

1472
00:54:05,308 --> 00:54:08,778
The man who wants to steal
every skill from all chefs in this world,

1473
00:54:08,845 --> 00:54:12,582
the evil hands of the show,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1474
00:54:15,051 --> 00:54:16,886
He's doing it again.

1475
00:54:16,953 --> 00:54:19,522
Do you believe Chef Ho-young has skills
that you can steal too?

1476
00:54:19,589 --> 00:54:21,424
There is no one

1477
00:54:21,491 --> 00:54:23,960
better than Ho-young to steal from.

1478
00:54:24,027 --> 00:54:27,764
I'm just wondering where I should aim
to leech off of him.

1479
00:54:27,831 --> 00:54:29,299
All you have to do is go for it?

1480
00:54:29,366 --> 00:54:31,167
It's like an oil pipeline.

1481
00:54:31,234 --> 00:54:32,469
-Like a rich mine?
-Yes.

1482
00:54:32,535 --> 00:54:34,204
-It's like an oil pipeline?
-Yes.

1483
00:54:34,271 --> 00:54:35,272
You'll strike oil.

1484
00:54:35,839 --> 00:54:37,974
THE MOMENT YOU STICK YOUR PIPE IN,
YOU'LL STRIKE OIL

1485
00:54:38,041 --> 00:54:40,543
There's a rumor
that Ho-young felt confident

1486
00:54:40,610 --> 00:54:43,580
from the moment he saw the order.

1487
00:54:43,647 --> 00:54:45,882
I also drink rather often,

1488
00:54:45,949 --> 00:54:47,717
and I relieve hangovers often too.

1489
00:54:47,784 --> 00:54:50,654
So I know very well
what you need to eat as a cure.

1490
00:54:50,720 --> 00:54:53,757
How many times a week do you drink?

1491
00:54:53,823 --> 00:54:54,991
I think

1492
00:54:55,058 --> 00:54:56,293
about five times a week.

1493
00:54:57,627 --> 00:54:58,762
THIS GUY NODS

1494
00:54:58,828 --> 00:55:00,530
Shouldn't he see a doctor?

1495
00:55:00,597 --> 00:55:02,966
-You shouldn't be here.
-You need treatment.

1496
00:55:03,033 --> 00:55:05,302
He should see a doctor first.

1497
00:55:05,368 --> 00:55:08,071
Maybe his tummy wasn't a cooking sack.

1498
00:55:08,138 --> 00:55:09,306
It's an alcohol sack.

1499
00:55:09,372 --> 00:55:10,507
HIDING HIS ALCOHOL SACK

1500
00:55:10,573 --> 00:55:11,941
-I see.
-He drinks a lot.

1501
00:55:12,008 --> 00:55:14,110
So you must cure your hangovers often.

1502
00:55:14,177 --> 00:55:17,881
There is a bit of fun in wondering
what I should eat in the morning.

1503
00:55:17,947 --> 00:55:19,616
So every meal you eat is a hangover cure?

1504
00:55:19,683 --> 00:55:22,319
It's always a cure
except for two days a week.

1505
00:55:22,385 --> 00:55:23,453
YOU CAN SAY THAT

1506
00:55:23,520 --> 00:55:26,856
I dare say that
I am the strongest contender

1507
00:55:26,923 --> 00:55:30,260
when it comes to bar snacks
and everything related to alcohol.

1508
00:55:30,327 --> 00:55:33,296
I also know a thing or two
about hangover cures.

1509
00:55:33,863 --> 00:55:35,699
I can say that I spent my thirties

1510
00:55:35,765 --> 00:55:38,968
switching between
hangover cures and drinks

1511
00:55:39,035 --> 00:55:40,904
on a constant juggling cycle.

1512
00:55:40,970 --> 00:55:42,238
Like juggling credit cards?

1513
00:55:42,305 --> 00:55:44,307
Some may have mistaken me
for being an alcoholic.

1514
00:55:44,374 --> 00:55:47,644
I'm also done figuring out
the kind of things you like to eat.

1515
00:55:47,711 --> 00:55:48,778
I see.

1516
00:55:48,845 --> 00:55:50,480
Not only are you making a hangover cure,

1517
00:55:51,047 --> 00:55:55,285
but it should also call for another drink
the moment he has a bite.

1518
00:55:56,119 --> 00:55:58,154
CHEF HO-YOUNG'S INGREDIENTS:
ABALONE, MANILA CLAM, SEAWEED FULVESCENS

1519
00:55:58,221 --> 00:56:00,290
GOMTANG MEAL KIT, SUNDAE-GUK MEAL KIT,
SHIITAKE, COOKED BRACKEN, SESAME

1520
00:56:00,357 --> 00:56:02,659
Now, Ho-young with three wins.

1521
00:56:02,726 --> 00:56:03,827
What are you making?

1522
00:56:03,893 --> 00:56:06,296
What I'm making today is called…

1523
00:56:06,363 --> 00:56:08,331
It's Hangover, Are You Bogging Off?

1524
00:56:08,398 --> 00:56:11,000
"Are you bogging off" means
"are you leaving" in a Jeju dialect.

1525
00:56:12,102 --> 00:56:15,605
That's why he's asking,
"Hangover, are you leaving?"

1526
00:56:15,672 --> 00:56:16,806
That must be it.

1527
00:56:16,873 --> 00:56:19,309
So, "Where are we bogging off to, Dad?"
is "Are we leaving, Dad?"

1528
00:56:19,376 --> 00:56:20,944
Yes, "Dad, are we bogging off?"

1529
00:56:21,010 --> 00:56:23,580
-Jeju dialect.
-The dish I prepared today

1530
00:56:23,646 --> 00:56:26,449
is a hangover soup in Jeju style.

1531
00:56:27,050 --> 00:56:29,252
I'm making two kinds of soup dishes.

1532
00:56:29,319 --> 00:56:32,021
First, I'll use abalone

1533
00:56:32,088 --> 00:56:35,658
with refreshing Manila clam broth.

1534
00:56:35,725 --> 00:56:40,697
The other one is something called
bracken hangover soup.

1535
00:56:40,764 --> 00:56:43,633
Hangovers disappear
once you begin to sweat.

1536
00:56:43,700 --> 00:56:47,437
Once you relieve your hangover,
you can grab another drink in round two.

1537
00:56:47,504 --> 00:56:49,406
I'll make
those hangover cure dishes for you.

1538
00:56:49,973 --> 00:56:51,307
LOVES IT

1539
00:56:51,374 --> 00:56:53,176
-So you're making two dishes?
-Yes.

1540
00:56:53,843 --> 00:56:54,811
I'm dying to try it.

1541
00:56:55,645 --> 00:56:57,847
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
TILEFISH, MANILA CLAM, SHRIMP

1542
00:56:57,914 --> 00:56:59,816
PERILLA OIL, CUCUMBER, BEAN SPROUT,
CILANTRO, SANSHO POWDER

1543
00:56:59,883 --> 00:57:03,253
Poong, you're up against him.
What are you making?

1544
00:57:03,319 --> 00:57:06,122
The name of my dish is this.

1545
00:57:06,823 --> 00:57:07,657
SLAM!

1546
00:57:08,691 --> 00:57:10,160
Follow Me to Tilefish.

1547
00:57:10,226 --> 00:57:11,094
LOL

1548
00:57:11,928 --> 00:57:13,463
Like, "Follow me to the rooftop."

1549
00:57:14,197 --> 00:57:15,298
COME UP TO THE ROOFTOP

1550
00:57:15,632 --> 00:57:16,833
WHAT NOW?

1551
00:57:16,900 --> 00:57:19,269
-Follow Me to Tilefish.
-Follow Me to Tilefish.

1552
00:57:19,335 --> 00:57:22,038
Yes, he said that
to the head of the disciplinary committee.

1553
00:57:22,105 --> 00:57:23,573
Like the line
from <i>Once Upon a Time in High School.</i>

1554
00:57:23,640 --> 00:57:24,541
Gosh.

1555
00:57:24,607 --> 00:57:26,476
-You're using tilefish?
-I am.

1556
00:57:26,543 --> 00:57:29,379
I plan to make…

1557
00:57:29,446 --> 00:57:31,347
-Yes?
-…a clear tilefish soup.

1558
00:57:31,414 --> 00:57:35,051
But I'll make it refreshing
in a Southeast Asian style.

1559
00:57:35,118 --> 00:57:37,754
-You also said you loved cilantro.
-I do.

1560
00:57:37,821 --> 00:57:39,823
So I'll add lots of cilantro
and make a hangover cure

1561
00:57:39,889 --> 00:57:41,758
in the Southeast Asian-style.

1562
00:57:41,825 --> 00:57:44,961
It'll taste wonderful if you add
some rice while you eat it.

1563
00:57:45,028 --> 00:57:46,696
-You can do that forever.
-Yes.

1564
00:57:46,763 --> 00:57:47,964
Gosh.

1565
00:57:48,031 --> 00:57:50,333
I heard you swore
that you wouldn't use MSG today.

1566
00:57:50,400 --> 00:57:51,568
-You're right.
-Is it true?

1567
00:57:51,634 --> 00:57:53,169
Especially for this round,

1568
00:57:53,236 --> 00:57:56,172
-I will not use any kind of MSG.
-Really?

1569
00:57:56,239 --> 00:57:58,775
I want to tickle Jong-hyuk's taste buds

1570
00:57:58,842 --> 00:58:01,244
with the natural flavors
from the ingredients.

1571
00:58:01,311 --> 00:58:02,545
So no chili oil?

1572
00:58:03,346 --> 00:58:05,748
-I need that. I'll be making that.
-He needs it.

1573
00:58:05,815 --> 00:58:08,084
Ho-young is making something
in Jeju-style,

1574
00:58:08,151 --> 00:58:11,588
while Poong is making something
in Southeast Asian-style.

1575
00:58:11,654 --> 00:58:14,023
Now, let us begin

1576
00:58:14,090 --> 00:58:17,994
the next round of cook-off,
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

1577
00:58:18,061 --> 00:58:21,331
Wanting to be Jong-hyuk's hangover twin,

1578
00:58:21,397 --> 00:58:22,899
Chef Jung Ho-young.

1579
00:58:23,633 --> 00:58:25,468
Hangover, strikeout!

1580
00:58:25,535 --> 00:58:29,472
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong
is after a hangover grand slam.

1581
00:58:29,539 --> 00:58:33,142
Who'll become the clean-up hitter
in the world of hangover cures?

1582
00:58:33,209 --> 00:58:36,279
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1583
00:58:36,779 --> 00:58:38,515
THE HANGOVER CURE ROUND BEGINS!

1584
00:58:39,449 --> 00:58:41,150
HANGOVER CURES

1585
00:58:41,551 --> 00:58:42,652
HO-YOUNG STARTS WITH ABALONES!

1586
00:58:42,719 --> 00:58:45,688
The dish needs to cure his hangover
but also make him crave more drinks.

1587
00:58:45,755 --> 00:58:49,225
They both added seafood. One uses
abalones, the other uses Manila clams.

1588
00:58:49,292 --> 00:58:50,894
Above all, soup is everything.

1589
00:58:50,960 --> 00:58:53,029
-Yes, it's important.
-They must do this well.

1590
00:58:53,096 --> 00:58:54,297
They're both using Manila clams.

1591
00:58:54,364 --> 00:58:56,566
Looks like they're both
using Manila clams.

1592
00:58:56,633 --> 00:58:58,134
-Cooking wine.
-Manila clam soup?

1593
00:58:58,201 --> 00:59:01,004
Manila clams taste so good
when stir-fried in cooking wine.

1594
00:59:01,437 --> 00:59:03,640
POONG GETS READY TO GRILL TILEFISH

1595
00:59:03,873 --> 00:59:05,708
Sesame oil, perilla oil.

1596
00:59:05,775 --> 00:59:06,910
Regular cooking oil.

1597
00:59:07,277 --> 00:59:08,578
1. MIX THREE OILS AND GRILL FISH

1598
00:59:08,645 --> 00:59:11,548
-There's the tilefish.
-It looks good.

1599
00:59:11,614 --> 00:59:12,916
SALT

1600
00:59:12,982 --> 00:59:14,250
He's using something.

1601
00:59:14,317 --> 00:59:17,086
Poong said he wouldn't use MSG,

1602
00:59:17,153 --> 00:59:20,390
but tilefish already has
lots of umami in itself.

1603
00:59:21,257 --> 00:59:23,760
That means he won't need to use MSG.

1604
00:59:23,826 --> 00:59:25,328
Is he making it crispy?

1605
00:59:25,395 --> 00:59:28,264
-Are those mushrooms?
-He's roasting shiitake.

1606
00:59:29,999 --> 00:59:31,534
-What's that?
-Clam broth?

1607
00:59:31,601 --> 00:59:33,570
-It's <i>gukbap</i> broth, the rice and soup.
-<i>Gukbap</i>?

1608
00:59:33,636 --> 00:59:35,972
-It looks like <i>sundae-gukbap</i> soup.
-Broth?

1609
00:59:36,039 --> 00:59:37,040
CLICK

1610
00:59:37,106 --> 00:59:39,142
-What are you grinding?
-Bracken?

1611
00:59:39,208 --> 00:59:40,543
I'm grinding bracken.

1612
00:59:40,610 --> 00:59:42,812
-Bracken.
-Why are you grinding those?

1613
00:59:42,879 --> 00:59:44,814
He added some offal too.

1614
00:59:44,881 --> 00:59:45,949
Why are you grinding bracken?

1615
00:59:46,015 --> 00:59:47,383
Oh, that must be Jeju style.

1616
00:59:47,984 --> 00:59:49,118
-Jeju style.
-Do you have to grind it?

1617
00:59:49,185 --> 00:59:51,721
-It's a thick soup.
-He's making bracken hangover soup.

1618
00:59:51,788 --> 00:59:53,222
I see. The Jeju style.

1619
00:59:53,289 --> 00:59:55,124
Ho-young ground some bracken.

1620
00:59:55,191 --> 00:59:56,893
Chili oil again? As always, chili oil.

1621
00:59:56,960 --> 00:59:59,329
The guest has changed,

1622
00:59:59,395 --> 01:00:00,997
so he's back to doing his usual.

1623
01:00:01,264 --> 01:00:02,298
WELCOME, IT'S YOUR FIRST TIME

1624
01:00:02,365 --> 01:00:03,733
We always see it, but not the guests.

1625
01:00:03,800 --> 01:00:05,602
The heat for the chili oil is too high.

1626
01:00:05,668 --> 01:00:06,603
DON'T WORRY

1627
01:00:07,203 --> 01:00:09,872
IT'LL COOL DOWN ONCE I POUR THIS IN!

1628
01:00:09,939 --> 01:00:11,107
<i>Sansho </i>pepper powder?

1629
01:00:11,174 --> 01:00:13,376
-That much?
-That's way too much.

1630
01:00:14,077 --> 01:00:16,145
-It's <i>sansho </i>pepper powder.
-<i>Sansho</i> powder.

1631
01:00:16,212 --> 01:00:20,550
Jong-hyuk gets disappointed
if these things get left out.

1632
01:00:21,451 --> 01:00:23,353
-He's using cilantro.
-Cilantro.

1633
01:00:23,620 --> 01:00:24,454
CUTS THE ROOTS

1634
01:00:24,754 --> 01:00:26,823
His dish will turn out
like Southeast Asian cuisine.

1635
01:00:26,889 --> 01:00:28,925
-The roots.
-You aren't throwing those away?

1636
01:00:28,992 --> 01:00:31,294
-He's using them.
-He's rubbing them instead.

1637
01:00:31,361 --> 01:00:33,529
They have a nice scent
and are often used to make broth.

1638
01:00:33,596 --> 01:00:35,264
I see. It's for the scent.

1639
01:00:35,698 --> 01:00:36,532
FLIP

1640
01:00:37,367 --> 01:00:40,036
HE ONLY BOILED THE BROTH FOR 2 MINUTES

1641
01:00:40,603 --> 01:00:42,171
Another set of clams?

1642
01:00:42,238 --> 01:00:43,873
-It's another batch.
-The second set.

1643
01:00:43,940 --> 01:00:47,677
I'll let him eat
the clams with bigger meat

1644
01:00:47,744 --> 01:00:51,214
and use the smaller ones
just to make the broth.

1645
01:00:51,280 --> 01:00:52,815
SMALLER CLAMS ARE FOR BROTH!

1646
01:00:53,449 --> 01:00:54,951
Why are you roasting the mushrooms?

1647
01:00:55,018 --> 01:00:57,820
Mushrooms give off more smell
once you roast them.

1648
01:00:57,887 --> 01:01:00,456
So I'm going to put it in the soup.

1649
01:01:01,557 --> 01:01:03,393
THE TAIL COMES APART…

1650
01:01:03,726 --> 01:01:06,095
IS IT HAPPENING AGAIN?

1651
01:01:06,162 --> 01:01:09,265
-Why are you flipping it like that?
-It's pretty thin.

1652
01:01:10,099 --> 01:01:13,369
Despite already seeing
Eun-yeong drop her fish,

1653
01:01:13,436 --> 01:01:16,572
he used tongs
and destroyed the fish in half.

1654
01:01:16,639 --> 01:01:18,341
"It won't happen to me."

1655
01:01:18,408 --> 01:01:19,776
-He doesn't mind.
-No.

1656
01:01:19,842 --> 01:01:21,511
Is he only making soup with the tilefish?

1657
01:01:21,577 --> 01:01:23,646
-Right.
-Why is he frying the fish?

1658
01:01:24,213 --> 01:01:25,648
-That's hot.
-Hot, hot, hot.

1659
01:01:26,149 --> 01:01:27,784
-It must be hot.
-Lower the heat.

1660
01:01:27,850 --> 01:01:29,952
-Lower the heat, Poong.
-It has to be hot.

1661
01:01:30,019 --> 01:01:31,988
I love that face he makes.

1662
01:01:32,055 --> 01:01:33,056
I can't lower the heat.

1663
01:01:33,122 --> 01:01:35,291
What did you just boil, Poong?

1664
01:01:35,358 --> 01:01:37,026
-Cilantro.
-Oh, cilantro.

1665
01:01:37,093 --> 01:01:38,227
Ten minutes and fifty seconds.

1666
01:01:38,294 --> 01:01:40,129
You have 10 minutes and 50 seconds.

1667
01:01:40,196 --> 01:01:42,331
You've used about five minutes.

1668
01:01:42,932 --> 01:01:45,868
5. BOIL GROUND BRACKEN
IN GOMTANG AND SUNDAE-GUK SOUP

1669
01:01:46,369 --> 01:01:47,336
AND THE CLAM BROTH?

1670
01:01:47,904 --> 01:01:52,542
6. ADD WATER, GARLIC, COOKING WINE,
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, AND GREEN ONION

1671
01:01:53,009 --> 01:01:54,911
THE BOILED CILANTRO

1672
01:01:55,278 --> 01:01:56,112
WRINGING IT OUT

1673
01:01:56,179 --> 01:01:57,180
It's hot.

1674
01:01:58,581 --> 01:01:59,949
Is he blending the boiled cilantro?

1675
01:02:00,016 --> 01:02:01,784
-Will he blend it?
-Why?

1676
01:02:01,851 --> 01:02:05,588
-Cooking oil is better than olive oil.
-Oh, he's…

1677
01:02:05,655 --> 01:02:07,156
-Is cooking oil better?
-No.

1678
01:02:07,223 --> 01:02:08,825
That olive oil is all right.

1679
01:02:08,891 --> 01:02:10,426
-It's okay.
-Use both.

1680
01:02:10,493 --> 01:02:11,694
You can mix them.

1681
01:02:11,761 --> 01:02:13,596
-Mix them.
-Mix just the one on the right.

1682
01:02:13,663 --> 01:02:15,264
BUT YOU STILL HAVE TO OPEN THE CAP

1683
01:02:15,331 --> 01:02:17,967
He mixes olive oil and cooking oil.

1684
01:02:18,034 --> 01:02:20,503
He's trying to make cilantro oil.

1685
01:02:20,770 --> 01:02:21,971
GOSU OIL

1686
01:02:22,038 --> 01:02:25,475
Sung-jun was trying to stop him from using
extra virgin olive oil. It smells strong.

1687
01:02:25,541 --> 01:02:27,710
He was worried that
the oil would overpower the cilantro.

1688
01:02:27,777 --> 01:02:29,512
BE CAREFUL

1689
01:02:29,579 --> 01:02:31,848
Does he have to boil it first?

1690
01:02:31,914 --> 01:02:33,916
If you blend fresh cilantro,

1691
01:02:33,983 --> 01:02:36,219
the color fades away
when the blender heats it up.

1692
01:02:36,285 --> 01:02:37,854
A-HA

1693
01:02:37,920 --> 01:02:39,589
And Poong knew that.

1694
01:02:39,655 --> 01:02:42,892
He actually asked me in the green room,
so I taught him that.

1695
01:02:43,960 --> 01:02:46,229
Chef Ho-young grabs an earthen pot.

1696
01:02:46,295 --> 01:02:49,999
-Manila clams get gummy when overcooked.
-They seem gummy.

1697
01:02:50,066 --> 01:02:54,170
He set aside the ones he'll eat
and used other ones to make broth.

1698
01:02:55,638 --> 01:02:58,141
I see. He used a different batch
for the broth.

1699
01:02:58,207 --> 01:02:59,675
He's so detailed.

1700
01:02:59,742 --> 01:03:00,877
He is.

1701
01:03:00,943 --> 01:03:01,778
FILLING IT WITH CLAM MEAT!

1702
01:03:02,545 --> 01:03:04,847
You now have ten minutes left.

1703
01:03:04,914 --> 01:03:06,215
-Five minutes are gone.
-He strains it

1704
01:03:06,282 --> 01:03:09,185
to get rid of the foam
and only get the clear soup.

1705
01:03:09,252 --> 01:03:10,953
-That is the right way?
-It's so clear.

1706
01:03:11,020 --> 01:03:12,955
-It looks nice.
-That looks good.

1707
01:03:14,223 --> 01:03:15,258
WASH AND PREP PARBOILED ABALONE

1708
01:03:15,324 --> 01:03:17,026
Ho-young parboiled abalone.

1709
01:03:17,093 --> 01:03:18,594
7. BOIL BROTH
WITH ABALONE, SOY SAUCE, AND SALT

1710
01:03:18,661 --> 01:03:21,164
He's putting lots of work into the soup.

1711
01:03:22,298 --> 01:03:24,233
ABSORBING HIS SKILLS RIGHT AWAY!

1712
01:03:24,834 --> 01:03:28,304
POONG ALSO USES MANILA CALM BROTH!

1713
01:03:28,905 --> 01:03:31,140
THERE IT IS! THAT FACE

1714
01:03:31,207 --> 01:03:32,809
He's pouring the broth there.

1715
01:03:32,875 --> 01:03:34,710
-Look at his face.
-Are you crying?

1716
01:03:35,278 --> 01:03:38,247
-You aren't crying, are you?
-No, I'm not.

1717
01:03:38,314 --> 01:03:40,950
He just copied him but made a mistake.

1718
01:03:41,017 --> 01:03:43,853
When you boil Manila clams,
you need to remove the foam on the top.

1719
01:03:43,920 --> 01:03:46,355
But he's using it
without filtering it out.

1720
01:03:47,323 --> 01:03:50,726
Yes, you're supposed to skim the foam off.

1721
01:03:50,793 --> 01:03:52,495
That's the kind of detail chefs have,

1722
01:03:52,562 --> 01:03:55,097
something you won't find in Poong.

1723
01:03:55,164 --> 01:03:56,365
I see.

1724
01:03:56,432 --> 01:03:57,266
DETAIL?

1725
01:03:57,333 --> 01:03:59,402
WHAT? LIKE THIS?

1726
01:03:59,936 --> 01:04:00,770
WHOOP!

1727
01:04:00,837 --> 01:04:02,772
He's now copying someone's performance!

1728
01:04:04,340 --> 01:04:05,508
Your hair!

1729
01:04:05,575 --> 01:04:07,710
-You got it on your hair.
-Your hair turned white.

1730
01:04:07,777 --> 01:04:09,579
-Good one.
-Like a particular someone.

1731
01:04:09,645 --> 01:04:11,814
-He knows how to cook like a cool guy.
-Sure.

1732
01:04:11,881 --> 01:04:16,118
You keep dissing Poong,
then compliment him too.

1733
01:04:16,185 --> 01:04:18,087
-Giving and taking.
-That's right.

1734
01:04:18,154 --> 01:04:21,023
He often gets influenced by Hyun-suk.

1735
01:04:21,090 --> 01:04:23,059
I think it might taste like <i>bugeo-guk.</i>

1736
01:04:24,427 --> 01:04:26,996
ROASTED SHIITAKE

1737
01:04:27,296 --> 01:04:28,865
INTO THE MANILA CLAM SOUP BOWL!

1738
01:04:28,931 --> 01:04:32,501
-What's that? Fulvescens?
-Seaweed fulvescens?

1739
01:04:32,568 --> 01:04:33,836
I had it in my fridge.

1740
01:04:34,871 --> 01:04:36,839
-That looks so good.
-He has lots of stuff.

1741
01:04:37,640 --> 01:04:39,709
He has an entire ocean in his fridge.

1742
01:04:41,244 --> 01:04:42,712
Rice.

1743
01:04:42,778 --> 01:04:45,081
You should strain the cilantro oil too.

1744
01:04:47,984 --> 01:04:50,620
A BRIGHT COLOR!

1745
01:04:50,686 --> 01:04:51,721
Good.

1746
01:04:53,055 --> 01:04:54,590
What are those? Shrimps?

1747
01:04:55,625 --> 01:04:57,627
-Cilantro.
-He's using more cilantro.

1748
01:04:57,693 --> 01:04:59,128
Watch your hand.

1749
01:04:59,195 --> 01:05:00,396
THANKS FOR ADDING ME

1750
01:05:00,463 --> 01:05:02,131
-Wow.
-Be careful.

1751
01:05:02,198 --> 01:05:04,634
-It's okay.
-He chops way too dangerously.

1752
01:05:04,700 --> 01:05:06,168
He chops cilantro into tiny pieces.

1753
01:05:06,235 --> 01:05:08,537
I said I liked cilantro,
but I think that's all he's using.

1754
01:05:08,604 --> 01:05:12,408
The fridge owner said
you seem to be using too much cilantro!

1755
01:05:12,475 --> 01:05:14,343
Isn't this more like cilantro hell?

1756
01:05:15,511 --> 01:05:17,780
-My gosh. What's that?
-A cucumber? Why?

1757
01:05:18,681 --> 01:05:20,483
-No!
-Cucumber in soup?

1758
01:05:20,549 --> 01:05:21,884
-Please!
-Cucumber soup?

1759
01:05:21,951 --> 01:05:23,986
It's because he didn't have radish.

1760
01:05:24,053 --> 01:05:27,523
-I'm using this for the refreshing taste.
-Cucumber instead of radish?

1761
01:05:27,590 --> 01:05:29,158
-Yes.
-Will it taste okay?

1762
01:05:29,225 --> 01:05:30,993
Is it because
this is Southeast Asian style?

1763
01:05:31,060 --> 01:05:33,195
Radish and cucumber seem very different.

1764
01:05:33,262 --> 01:05:35,831
Cucumber can also give
a refreshing flavor.

1765
01:05:35,898 --> 01:05:37,500
-It's often used in Chinese cuisine.
-Yes.

1766
01:05:37,566 --> 01:05:39,669
I think cucumber should be fine.

1767
01:05:40,036 --> 01:05:40,937
ATTENTION!

1768
01:05:41,304 --> 01:05:43,272
ADDING STARCH WATER
INTO BRACKEN HANGOVER SOUP!

1769
01:05:43,506 --> 01:05:45,641
8. ADD STARCH WATER
TO BRACKEN HANGOVER SOUP

1770
01:05:45,708 --> 01:05:46,976
VISCOUS

1771
01:05:47,043 --> 01:05:49,278
-Five minutes, Jung-hwan.
-Yes.

1772
01:05:49,345 --> 01:05:50,913
MOUTH-WATERING

1773
01:05:50,980 --> 01:05:52,248
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

1774
01:05:52,315 --> 01:05:54,150
The soup is the key.

1775
01:05:54,216 --> 01:05:56,919
-They look the same.
-He has three different soups.

1776
01:05:56,986 --> 01:05:59,722
-It looks like a soup battle.
-Yes.

1777
01:05:59,789 --> 01:06:02,124
Chef Ho-young is boiling
three pots of different soups.

1778
01:06:02,191 --> 01:06:03,659
This was the soup he worked on.

1779
01:06:03,726 --> 01:06:05,861
MAKING CUTS!

1780
01:06:05,928 --> 01:06:07,697
-Did you mix ground bracken?
-Yes.

1781
01:06:07,763 --> 01:06:10,466
Just like Ujin Haejangguk in Jeju.

1782
01:06:10,533 --> 01:06:11,801
Bracken hangover soup.

1783
01:06:11,867 --> 01:06:14,870
I added bracken and some starch.

1784
01:06:14,937 --> 01:06:18,074
8. PUT ROASTED SHIITAKE,
SEAWEED FULVESCENS, AND ABALONE IN A BOWL

1785
01:06:18,140 --> 01:06:19,675
The thing with Poong is,

1786
01:06:19,742 --> 01:06:22,945
I'm still unsure
how these cucumber pieces will play out.

1787
01:06:23,012 --> 01:06:24,613
Can you try the soup?

1788
01:06:24,680 --> 01:06:26,816
-The cucumber?
-There are 4 minutes and 52 seconds left.

1789
01:06:26,882 --> 01:06:29,685
-It can taste refreshing and delicious.
-What's the situation?

1790
01:06:29,752 --> 01:06:32,822
-It smells like Southeast Asian cuisine.
-I see.

1791
01:06:33,389 --> 01:06:35,358
I'll get it from the area
near the cucumber.

1792
01:06:35,424 --> 01:06:36,525
TILEFISH SOUP PROGRESS REPORT

1793
01:06:37,927 --> 01:06:40,296
Can he follow the tilefish?

1794
01:06:41,063 --> 01:06:42,298
Are we going to Southeast Asia?

1795
01:06:43,499 --> 01:06:44,333
Cucumber!

1796
01:06:46,202 --> 01:06:47,336
It's a bit fishy for me.

1797
01:06:47,403 --> 01:06:48,671
-What?
-Goodness.

1798
01:06:48,738 --> 01:06:51,807
CUCUMBER WASN'T THE PROBLEM!

1799
01:06:51,874 --> 01:06:54,543
-This sounds like trouble.
-Isn't that right?

1800
01:06:54,610 --> 01:06:55,978
-It's okay.
-Is it okay, Poong?

1801
01:06:56,045 --> 01:06:58,781
-I like the depth of the flavor.
-Is that ginger?

1802
01:06:58,848 --> 01:07:00,449
I think it's the oil flavor

1803
01:07:00,516 --> 01:07:02,585
that was left on the pan
when he fried the fish.

1804
01:07:02,651 --> 01:07:04,253
-Do you get what I mean?
-That's not good.

1805
01:07:04,320 --> 01:07:05,921
-That musty smell.
-Yes!

1806
01:07:05,988 --> 01:07:08,758
Chinese cuisine
often makes broth like this,

1807
01:07:08,824 --> 01:07:10,126
and it's better to deep-fry it.

1808
01:07:10,192 --> 01:07:12,161
It's okay.

1809
01:07:12,228 --> 01:07:14,997
-He'll throw in lots of cilantro.
-I hope that eliminates the smell.

1810
01:07:15,064 --> 01:07:16,365
It'll change with cilantro.

1811
01:07:16,432 --> 01:07:19,535
POURING JUST THE SOUP INTO A CAST-IRON PAN

1812
01:07:19,935 --> 01:07:21,704
Can't he use a strainer?

1813
01:07:21,771 --> 01:07:23,739
-I know, I wish he'd do that.
-Why won't he?

1814
01:07:23,939 --> 01:07:27,543
8. MOVE THE SOUP, SHRIMP,
AND MANILA CLAM, THEN BOIL

1815
01:07:29,011 --> 01:07:31,147
BRACKEN, GREEN ONION

1816
01:07:31,981 --> 01:07:33,783
GRINDING ONE MORE TIME

1817
01:07:33,849 --> 01:07:35,584
-Chef Ho-young's soup.
-Is this it?

1818
01:07:36,152 --> 01:07:37,620
-That one first.
-This one?

1819
01:07:37,686 --> 01:07:38,721
Yes, that one.

1820
01:07:38,788 --> 01:07:41,590
-This isn't ready yet.
-Yes, he's still adding bracken.

1821
01:07:41,657 --> 01:07:44,360
I wonder what this is like.

1822
01:07:44,427 --> 01:07:45,861
He put lots of work into it.

1823
01:07:47,263 --> 01:07:48,531
What do you think?

1824
01:07:48,597 --> 01:07:50,633
Does the soup have a deep flavor?

1825
01:07:50,699 --> 01:07:51,801
Gosh.

1826
01:07:51,867 --> 01:07:53,869
Manila clams are wriggling
30 m underwater.

1827
01:07:54,737 --> 01:07:56,105
-Goodness.
-I see.

1828
01:07:56,172 --> 01:07:57,406
I'M CURIOUS

1829
01:07:57,473 --> 01:07:59,708
-I like it.
-It seemed like plain water.

1830
01:07:59,775 --> 01:08:01,143
There's a bit of sweetness.

1831
01:08:01,210 --> 01:08:02,611
It must be the natural clam flavor.

1832
01:08:03,612 --> 01:08:04,680
Not from any condiments.

1833
01:08:04,747 --> 01:08:06,148
BRINGING OUT SWEETNESS WITHOUT SUGAR

1834
01:08:06,215 --> 01:08:07,883
-That sounds great.
-Yes, it is.

1835
01:08:08,751 --> 01:08:11,320
Poong's chili oil is finished.

1836
01:08:11,887 --> 01:08:13,355
SOY SAUCE

1837
01:08:13,756 --> 01:08:17,760
9. MIX SOY SAUCE, SANSHO PEPPER POWDER,
VINEGAR, AND CHILI OIL

1838
01:08:18,027 --> 01:08:19,829
ANOTHER DASH OF SANSHO PEPPER POWDER!

1839
01:08:20,396 --> 01:08:21,664
That's too much.

1840
01:08:21,730 --> 01:08:23,866
-Poong scoops something out.
-What is it?

1841
01:08:23,933 --> 01:08:26,869
-What happened?
-I added too much <i>sansho</i>.

1842
01:08:26,936 --> 01:08:28,871
IT LOOKS GREAT AT A GLANCE

1843
01:08:28,938 --> 01:08:30,873
-It's like white <i>jjamppong</i>.
-It is.

1844
01:08:30,940 --> 01:08:32,374
-Nagasaki <i>champon</i>.
-Nagasaki.

1845
01:08:32,441 --> 01:08:34,410
Are you not using the fish?

1846
01:08:34,477 --> 01:08:36,679
-Are you not using these?
-I am.

1847
01:08:36,745 --> 01:08:38,948
-He's using just the meat.
-Just the meat.

1848
01:08:40,649 --> 01:08:41,750
-It must be hot.
-I'm fine.

1849
01:08:41,817 --> 01:08:43,018
It's falling apart.

1850
01:08:43,085 --> 01:08:46,522
-He moves the fish with his hands.
-Yes, Poong moves the fish.

1851
01:08:46,589 --> 01:08:48,824
He probably has a tool.
Why is he using his hands?

1852
01:08:48,891 --> 01:08:51,460
To remove as many bones as possible.

1853
01:08:51,527 --> 01:08:52,862
MOVED

1854
01:08:52,928 --> 01:08:54,363
I'm telling you! It's hot.

1855
01:08:54,430 --> 01:08:55,965
A minute and 30 seconds.

1856
01:08:56,031 --> 01:08:57,399
A minute and 30 seconds.
You're almost done.

1857
01:08:57,466 --> 01:08:59,535
No matter how hot it is,

1858
01:08:59,602 --> 01:09:01,770
he's sacrificing his hands
for Jong-hyuk's hangover.

1859
01:09:01,837 --> 01:09:04,907
-A minute and ten seconds.
-Now, time for cilantro.

1860
01:09:04,974 --> 01:09:06,342
It's cilantro soup.

1861
01:09:06,408 --> 01:09:07,643
-Cilantro.
-One minute!

1862
01:09:07,710 --> 01:09:09,111
DROPPING

1863
01:09:09,178 --> 01:09:11,180
TA-DA!

1864
01:09:11,247 --> 01:09:12,248
And this one.

1865
01:09:12,781 --> 01:09:14,283
He's adding more oil.

1866
01:09:14,350 --> 01:09:16,418
He adds cilantro and cilantro oil.

1867
01:09:16,919 --> 01:09:18,220
HO-YOUNG FINISHES UP TOO!

1868
01:09:18,387 --> 01:09:20,089
GREEN ONION, CHEONGYANG PEPPER

1869
01:09:21,390 --> 01:09:23,792
ROASTED SHIITAKE, SEAWEED FULVESCENS,
ABALONE, AND GREEN ONION

1870
01:09:24,593 --> 01:09:25,928
THE EARTHEN POT WITH CLAM MEAT

1871
01:09:26,195 --> 01:09:28,697
POUR BRACKEN HANGOVER SOUP INTO THE POT!

1872
01:09:29,098 --> 01:09:30,466
1. TOP SOUP WITH RED PEPPER POWDER,
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, SESAME

1873
01:09:30,533 --> 01:09:32,735
Ho-young works hard on the earthen pot.

1874
01:09:32,801 --> 01:09:35,237
This is something new.

1875
01:09:35,304 --> 01:09:36,639
-Yes.
-It's thick.

1876
01:09:36,705 --> 01:09:38,874
That's such a different color.

1877
01:09:39,475 --> 01:09:40,910
-Thirty seconds.
-Okay.

1878
01:09:40,976 --> 01:09:42,978
These are both soups,
so finish first to have an advantage.

1879
01:09:43,045 --> 01:09:44,413
-That's a given.
-Rice.

1880
01:09:44,480 --> 01:09:46,248
-Rice.
-Can you grab this?

1881
01:09:46,315 --> 01:09:47,683
What about this?

1882
01:09:47,750 --> 01:09:48,651
What do I do with it?

1883
01:09:48,717 --> 01:09:50,052
Twenty seconds.

1884
01:09:50,119 --> 01:09:51,320
There's no time. Wrap up.

1885
01:09:51,387 --> 01:09:53,322
-Ho-young finishes!
-Ho-young is done!

1886
01:09:53,389 --> 01:09:54,490
-Poong?
-Ho-young finishes.

1887
01:09:54,557 --> 01:09:56,892
He's already done,
so take your time, Poong.

1888
01:09:56,959 --> 01:09:57,860
Twenty seconds.

1889
01:09:58,527 --> 01:09:59,528
There's no time. Wrap up.

1890
01:09:59,762 --> 01:10:01,263
INTO THE BOWL

1891
01:10:02,498 --> 01:10:03,866
IN A RUSH

1892
01:10:04,767 --> 01:10:05,834
-…Poong!
-Poong!

1893
01:10:06,535 --> 01:10:08,270
-The rice is ready.
-Put it there.

1894
01:10:08,337 --> 01:10:09,171
Eight.

1895
01:10:09,238 --> 01:10:10,072
TOSSES THE RICE

1896
01:10:10,673 --> 01:10:12,641
TRIGGERS HIS LAUGHTER

1897
01:10:12,708 --> 01:10:14,376
-Four. Three
-Four.

1898
01:10:14,443 --> 01:10:16,845
-Poong finishes too.
-Poong is done.

1899
01:10:17,379 --> 01:10:18,547
Poong is done too.

1900
01:10:18,614 --> 01:10:20,049
As always, his rice

1901
01:10:20,115 --> 01:10:22,585
-is presented as a mess.
-Yes.

1902
01:10:22,651 --> 01:10:23,786
Did he throw it in there?

1903
01:10:23,852 --> 01:10:25,221
IT'S OKAY,
IT'S THE GUESTS' FIRST TIME

1904
01:10:25,287 --> 01:10:26,488
THE GRANDPA'S LAUGHTER TRIGGER

1905
01:10:26,555 --> 01:10:28,924
If he adds soup to fish that's frying,

1906
01:10:29,491 --> 01:10:31,026
-doesn't it make it greasy?
-Yes.

1907
01:10:31,093 --> 01:10:32,895
The grease might make the dish better.

1908
01:10:32,962 --> 01:10:34,463
It's hard to imagine.

1909
01:10:34,530 --> 01:10:36,265
Hey, what is that?

1910
01:10:37,233 --> 01:10:38,300
Gosh, the smell.

1911
01:10:42,104 --> 01:10:43,005
JEALOUS

1912
01:10:43,072 --> 01:10:44,273
It's a fight between soups.

1913
01:10:44,340 --> 01:10:46,275
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

1914
01:10:46,342 --> 01:10:49,278
Both hangover cures
for Jong-hyuk were finished.

1915
01:10:49,345 --> 01:10:50,212
FULL OF HOPE

1916
01:10:50,279 --> 01:10:51,480
How do you feel?

1917
01:10:51,547 --> 01:10:53,515
Many unexpected ingredients

1918
01:10:53,582 --> 01:10:57,186
were used by them from my fridge.

1919
01:10:57,253 --> 01:10:58,254
I'm also wondering

1920
01:10:58,320 --> 01:11:00,389
is that dish really something edible?

1921
01:11:01,390 --> 01:11:03,459
-Can you eat it?
-Is it edible?

1922
01:11:03,525 --> 01:11:05,561
It seems quite new.

1923
01:11:05,628 --> 01:11:08,163
-It looks like cilantro soup.
-Yes.

1924
01:11:08,230 --> 01:11:10,833
Chef Ho-young finished cooking first,

1925
01:11:10,899 --> 01:11:13,636
<i>so please first try</i>
<i>Hangover, Are You Bogging Off?</i>

1926
01:11:13,702 --> 01:11:15,104
CLEAR SOUP WITH MUSHROOM AND SEAFOOD

1927
01:11:15,971 --> 01:11:18,807
JEJU-STYLE THICK BRACKEN HANGOVER SOUP

1928
01:11:19,575 --> 01:11:22,978
CHEF JUNG HO-YOUNG'S
HANGOVER, ARE YOU BOGGING OFF?

1929
01:11:23,045 --> 01:11:24,446
It looks so good.

1930
01:11:24,513 --> 01:11:26,015
He made bracken hangover soup.

1931
01:11:26,081 --> 01:11:28,984
Let us know if you crave a drink
as you eat it.

1932
01:11:29,051 --> 01:11:31,654
-I'm already craving some as I look at it.
-Already?

1933
01:11:31,720 --> 01:11:32,821
I see.

1934
01:11:33,389 --> 01:11:35,291
-He added some starch too.
-Try it.

1935
01:11:35,357 --> 01:11:37,259
That's a perfect hangover cure.

1936
01:11:37,326 --> 01:11:40,696
Is a hangover soup
made with ground bracken a thing?

1937
01:11:40,763 --> 01:11:43,432
-It's in Jeju.
-It's Jeju-style.

1938
01:11:44,099 --> 01:11:46,068
I've never seen it before.

1939
01:11:46,135 --> 01:11:48,103
I think he ground sesame in here too.

1940
01:11:48,937 --> 01:11:50,706
-The soup…
-I'm curious.

1941
01:11:50,773 --> 01:11:52,808
…smells similar to <i>sundae-guk.</i>

1942
01:11:52,875 --> 01:11:55,311
<i>Chueo-tang</i>, loach soup,
is also made with ground loaches.

1943
01:11:55,377 --> 01:11:57,613
His stomach must be quite sour now.

1944
01:11:57,680 --> 01:12:00,449
He had a few drinks of soju
in the previous cook-off.

1945
01:12:00,516 --> 01:12:02,084
Or the hangover from yesterday.

1946
01:12:02,651 --> 01:12:04,753
VERY CURIOUS

1947
01:12:05,321 --> 01:12:07,323
SMACKING

1948
01:12:07,389 --> 01:12:08,857
Gosh, this is…

1949
01:12:08,924 --> 01:12:10,592
Something keeps…

1950
01:12:10,659 --> 01:12:14,663
I taste some sesame and something else.
What else is in this?

1951
01:12:14,730 --> 01:12:17,199
<i>I added some ground pork too.</i>

1952
01:12:17,266 --> 01:12:19,068
It tastes like bracken soup.

1953
01:12:20,436 --> 01:12:21,804
Does it taste strong?

1954
01:12:21,870 --> 01:12:23,906
-No, it's perfect.
-It is?

1955
01:12:23,972 --> 01:12:25,274
I actually like my food bland.

1956
01:12:26,742 --> 01:12:27,576
A bit bland?

1957
01:12:27,643 --> 01:12:30,579
-You often drink clear soup as a cure.
-I do.

1958
01:12:30,646 --> 01:12:33,015
But I eat this often when I go to Jeju.

1959
01:12:33,082 --> 01:12:34,683
THIS SOUP IS AN EXCEPTION!

1960
01:12:34,750 --> 01:12:36,018
You feel the alcohol leaving.

1961
01:12:36,085 --> 01:12:37,252
ANOTHER BITE TO RELIEVE SOME MORE

1962
01:12:37,853 --> 01:12:39,655
FROWN

1963
01:12:39,722 --> 01:12:42,558
He's enjoying the food with a frown.

1964
01:12:43,425 --> 01:12:45,361
Would you like
another glass of the red cap?

1965
01:12:46,328 --> 01:12:47,162
SLAM!

1966
01:12:47,696 --> 01:12:48,764
-Go?
-Go.

1967
01:12:50,032 --> 01:12:51,233
-He gave us the go.
-Go.

1968
01:12:51,300 --> 01:12:53,535
-Grab another bottle of the red cap.
-He's craving a drink!

1969
01:12:54,103 --> 01:12:56,538
BURNING

1970
01:12:57,306 --> 01:12:59,575
Should I turn the heat off?

1971
01:12:59,641 --> 01:13:02,311
-I'm worried that it'll boil down.
-More water?

1972
01:13:02,378 --> 01:13:05,447
Can you turn the heat off
and add 100 ml more water?

1973
01:13:05,514 --> 01:13:07,516
It keeps boiling down.

1974
01:13:07,583 --> 01:13:11,420
The heat was stronger than he thought.

1975
01:13:11,487 --> 01:13:14,256
-That looks like algae bloom.
-This is practically…

1976
01:13:14,323 --> 01:13:16,859
-It looks like the algae bloom.
-Give it a moment.

1977
01:13:16,925 --> 01:13:21,497
He was relieving his hangover in a hurry…

1978
01:13:21,563 --> 01:13:24,333
-Another swirl.
-…then craved another drink.

1979
01:13:25,467 --> 01:13:27,836
-It made him crave a drink.
-Yes.

1980
01:13:28,971 --> 01:13:30,906
It really does. I mean it.

1981
01:13:30,973 --> 01:13:33,642
-While relieving your hangover?
-I do this when I'm in Jeju.

1982
01:13:33,709 --> 01:13:36,445
I said I liked clear soup,

1983
01:13:36,512 --> 01:13:38,480
so he must've been very confident

1984
01:13:38,547 --> 01:13:40,349
when he served me this soup.

1985
01:13:41,784 --> 01:13:44,420
-This time…
-The Manila clam soup.

1986
01:13:44,486 --> 01:13:46,355
The fulvescens is hotter than you think,

1987
01:13:46,422 --> 01:13:47,956
-so be careful.
-Okay.

1988
01:13:48,023 --> 01:13:50,025
-Now--
-I had the seaweed fulvescens at home,

1989
01:13:50,092 --> 01:13:53,929
but didn't know what to do with it,
so it had been giving me a headache.

1990
01:13:53,996 --> 01:13:55,998
I was told to wash it first,

1991
01:13:56,064 --> 01:13:58,734
and it seemed like I needed a strainer.

1992
01:13:58,801 --> 01:14:01,937
So when I used it,
it would escape through all the time.

1993
01:14:02,004 --> 01:14:05,808
It keeps flowing out like a ghost's hair.
I try my best to hold it in,

1994
01:14:05,874 --> 01:14:08,277
but I always end up
throwing away about a third.

1995
01:14:08,343 --> 01:14:10,179
-How do you wash fulvescens?
-How do you do it?

1996
01:14:10,245 --> 01:14:13,682
You should put it in a huge bowl,

1997
01:14:13,749 --> 01:14:17,486
pick out some impurities with chopsticks,
then dry it in a strainer.

1998
01:14:17,553 --> 01:14:18,987
So after you draw the water?

1999
01:14:19,054 --> 01:14:20,789
-That's how you pick them out.
-Yes.

2000
01:14:20,856 --> 01:14:23,725
-Did you use running water?
-Yes. I didn't know.

2001
01:14:24,359 --> 01:14:26,462
The seaweed fulvescens soup.

2002
01:14:27,429 --> 01:14:29,731
WHAT'S MANILA CLAM SOUP LIKE?

2003
01:14:29,798 --> 01:14:31,266
I wonder what this is like.

2004
01:14:33,135 --> 01:14:34,670
He savors it.

2005
01:14:34,736 --> 01:14:37,673
I just felt a dash of the ocean
in my nose.

2006
01:14:38,607 --> 01:14:40,042
But…

2007
01:14:40,108 --> 01:14:42,244
Is it because of seaweed fulvescens?

2008
01:14:43,011 --> 01:14:45,581
I can also taste something quite bitter.

2009
01:14:45,647 --> 01:14:47,850
-It's bitter?
-Yes, a bit.

2010
01:14:47,916 --> 01:14:49,151
Was it intentional?

2011
01:14:49,751 --> 01:14:50,719
Is it cooking wine?

2012
01:14:51,987 --> 01:14:53,956
-That can't be it.
-Was the seaweed too old?

2013
01:14:54,990 --> 01:14:56,758
-What?
-He says it's a bit bitter.

2014
01:14:56,825 --> 01:14:58,460
Bitter sounds negative.

2015
01:14:58,527 --> 01:15:01,163
-Bitter?
-Ho-young tries the seaweed.

2016
01:15:01,230 --> 01:15:03,198
-It's fine.
-What is it?

2017
01:15:03,265 --> 01:15:05,634
-The seaweed is fine, right?
-Yes.

2018
01:15:05,701 --> 01:15:08,237
Then your tongue must be unwell.
You drank too much.

2019
01:15:08,303 --> 01:15:10,405
HE ALREADY LOST HIS SENSE OF TASTE

2020
01:15:10,472 --> 01:15:12,641
May I try it as a fellow drinker?

2021
01:15:12,708 --> 01:15:13,775
It should taste only sweet.

2022
01:15:13,842 --> 01:15:15,511
THAT'S ODD…

2023
01:15:15,577 --> 01:15:16,411
It tastes bitter?

2024
01:15:16,478 --> 01:15:19,047
A fellow drinker, Jung-hwan,
tries the soup.

2025
01:15:19,114 --> 01:15:20,482
WHAT DOES JUNG-HWAN THINK?

2026
01:15:20,549 --> 01:15:22,084
-Is it bitter?
-Isn't it a little bitter?

2027
01:15:23,151 --> 01:15:24,586
It's not that it's bitter.

2028
01:15:25,721 --> 01:15:29,157
When there's too much seafood
like seaweed and clams,

2029
01:15:29,224 --> 01:15:33,428
-the umami becomes too strong.
-And that can feel bitter.

2030
01:15:33,495 --> 01:15:35,764
I think it can feel that way.

2031
01:15:35,831 --> 01:15:37,065
So you don't like this?

2032
01:15:37,132 --> 01:15:39,067
IS THE MANILA CLAM SOUP OUT?

2033
01:15:39,468 --> 01:15:42,104
-That's what he means.
-For now… For now…

2034
01:15:42,170 --> 01:15:43,572
-Chef Ho-young.
-Yes?

2035
01:15:43,639 --> 01:15:47,175
Which soup is the main dish?
The bracken soup? The seaweed soup?

2036
01:15:47,242 --> 01:15:48,076
Bracken.

2037
01:15:48,143 --> 01:15:50,178
You can push the other soup aside.

2038
01:15:50,245 --> 01:15:51,847
-That clam soup…
-It's just for decoration?

2039
01:15:51,914 --> 01:15:54,883
-It was like a refreshment.
-It was on the house.

2040
01:15:54,950 --> 01:15:56,718
-A plus one.
-Like a side dish.

2041
01:15:56,785 --> 01:15:57,953
-It was on the house.
-A drink.

2042
01:15:58,020 --> 01:16:00,355
Is it something I can drink
when I get thirsty?

2043
01:16:00,422 --> 01:16:03,325
Next, Follow Me to Tilefish.

2044
01:16:03,392 --> 01:16:04,960
-This one…
-It looks like algae bloom soup.

2045
01:16:05,027 --> 01:16:07,362
-We might find a frog in there.
-A frog?

2046
01:16:07,429 --> 01:16:08,630
Like a lily pond.

2047
01:16:08,697 --> 01:16:11,033
-It looks like a frog would frolic around.
-Yes, like a pond.

2048
01:16:11,099 --> 01:16:12,868
I can even see a toad.

2049
01:16:12,935 --> 01:16:13,902
WHAT'S THE FROG POND LIKE?

2050
01:16:13,969 --> 01:16:16,305
Follow Me to Tilefish,
aka Algae Bloom Soup.

2051
01:16:17,272 --> 01:16:21,510
TILEFISH AND MANILA CLAM BROTH
WITH A HEAP OF CILANTRO

2052
01:16:22,077 --> 01:16:25,080
SERVED WITH SANSHO CHILI OIL

2053
01:16:25,814 --> 01:16:29,217
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
FOLLOW ME TO TILEFISH

2054
01:16:29,284 --> 01:16:33,488
You were grilling the tilefish in a pan,
poured the broth,

2055
01:16:33,555 --> 01:16:36,124
and then pulled the fish out, but why?

2056
01:16:36,191 --> 01:16:39,494
First, I had to extract
the flavor from the fish.

2057
01:16:40,062 --> 01:16:42,764
So I grilled it in perilla oil
and sesame oil,

2058
01:16:42,831 --> 01:16:44,967
then poured the Manila clam broth

2059
01:16:45,033 --> 01:16:46,835
to bring out all of its flavors.

2060
01:16:46,902 --> 01:16:48,370
-I see.
-And that's this soup?

2061
01:16:48,437 --> 01:16:49,705
-Yes.
-I see.

2062
01:16:49,771 --> 01:16:51,773
And you added the fish meat.

2063
01:16:51,840 --> 01:16:53,075
-That's right.
-Yes.

2064
01:16:53,141 --> 01:16:55,243
He's saying he gave it a bit of a change.

2065
01:16:55,310 --> 01:16:57,045
First off, it definitely smells

2066
01:16:57,112 --> 01:16:59,681
-like Southeast Asian cuisine.
-Does it really?

2067
01:16:59,748 --> 01:17:01,249
It smells like Southeast Asian cuisine.

2068
01:17:01,316 --> 01:17:02,317
A SLURP

2069
01:17:02,384 --> 01:17:03,452
Southeast Asian hangover soup.

2070
01:17:04,753 --> 01:17:07,122
LOOKING AROUND?

2071
01:17:07,189 --> 01:17:08,457
FROWNING?

2072
01:17:08,523 --> 01:17:09,458
CHUCKLE

2073
01:17:09,725 --> 01:17:11,860
ALL HE CAN DO IS LAUGH

2074
01:17:11,927 --> 01:17:14,863
I laughed because I know
he's the type who can't hide his face.

2075
01:17:14,930 --> 01:17:17,899
-Is something weird?
-It's his face.

2076
01:17:17,966 --> 01:17:20,035
-No, it's not that.
-It's not that?

2077
01:17:20,102 --> 01:17:21,269
That's not it?

2078
01:17:21,336 --> 01:17:22,504
DENIES AND TASTES IT AGAIN

2079
01:17:22,571 --> 01:17:23,605
Is it unique?

2080
01:17:24,806 --> 01:17:25,674
First of all,

2081
01:17:25,741 --> 01:17:27,476
I mentioned that I love cilantro, right?

2082
01:17:27,542 --> 01:17:28,910
Isn't it too much?

2083
01:17:28,977 --> 01:17:30,212
I love it right now.

2084
01:17:30,278 --> 01:17:32,414
-You love it?
-You said he added too much.

2085
01:17:32,481 --> 01:17:34,650
You thought it was a bit too much.

2086
01:17:34,716 --> 01:17:36,785
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

2087
01:17:36,852 --> 01:17:39,087
We said a frog could live in there.

2088
01:17:39,154 --> 01:17:40,555
With all seriousness,

2089
01:17:40,622 --> 01:17:42,758
I felt like
I was in Joseon before this round,

2090
01:17:42,824 --> 01:17:45,927
then suddenly, I got into a time machine
and flew to Southeast Asia.

2091
01:17:47,496 --> 01:17:48,797
It feels hot,

2092
01:17:48,864 --> 01:17:51,400
-as if I'm about to sweat.
-You're sweating?

2093
01:17:51,466 --> 01:17:53,235
-That means you're sobering up.
-Yes.

2094
01:17:53,301 --> 01:17:57,673
-The algae bloom soup.
-This is something I've never had before.

2095
01:17:57,739 --> 01:17:59,508
A COMPLETELY NEW TASTE

2096
01:17:59,574 --> 01:18:01,343
He takes another drink.

2097
01:18:01,410 --> 01:18:02,644
AND MAKES YOU WANT TO DRINK

2098
01:18:02,711 --> 01:18:04,279
Next, please try

2099
01:18:04,346 --> 01:18:05,981
Webtoon Artist Poong's signature dish,

2100
01:18:06,048 --> 01:18:07,282
"tilt rice."

2101
01:18:07,349 --> 01:18:09,317
-What rice?
-Tilt rice.

2102
01:18:09,384 --> 01:18:11,253
Because the rice is tilted.

2103
01:18:11,319 --> 01:18:13,889
He always serves it tilted like that.

2104
01:18:13,955 --> 01:18:16,925
It's his signature dish.
He always throws the rice in a hurry.

2105
01:18:16,992 --> 01:18:19,695
-It's his signature dish.
-It looks like half a bowl.

2106
01:18:19,761 --> 01:18:22,297
-It's an artistic depiction.
-An artistic depiction.

2107
01:18:22,364 --> 01:18:24,866
And this chili oil and soy sauce.

2108
01:18:24,933 --> 01:18:26,535
That sauce seems addictive too.

2109
01:18:26,601 --> 01:18:28,470
I'll try it with some chili oil.

2110
01:18:29,404 --> 01:18:32,074
It looks like he's starting to sweat.

2111
01:18:33,542 --> 01:18:34,876
CURIOUS

2112
01:18:34,943 --> 01:18:36,311
What's it like with chili oil?

2113
01:18:37,412 --> 01:18:38,580
It's even better.

2114
01:18:38,647 --> 01:18:40,582
Really? Are you serious?

2115
01:18:41,149 --> 01:18:42,584
-Really?
-Yes.

2116
01:18:42,651 --> 01:18:44,119
It's an emergency.

2117
01:18:44,186 --> 01:18:46,188
He's so unexpectedly good at times.

2118
01:18:47,255 --> 01:18:48,523
MIXING RICE RIGHT AWAY

2119
01:18:48,590 --> 01:18:49,624
He's starting to mix rice.

2120
01:18:49,691 --> 01:18:50,992
-The tilt rice.
-Yes.

2121
01:18:51,059 --> 01:18:53,995
And he eats it like hangover soup.

2122
01:18:54,563 --> 01:18:56,398
He mixed rice
into the Southeast Asian soup.

2123
01:18:56,465 --> 01:18:58,300
What's it like with rice?

2124
01:18:59,634 --> 01:19:01,036
Was it not so good?

2125
01:19:01,103 --> 01:19:02,204
One more drink, please.

2126
01:19:02,904 --> 01:19:04,740
"One more drink, please."

2127
01:19:04,806 --> 01:19:06,274
A POSITIVE SIGNAL?

2128
01:19:06,341 --> 01:19:10,412
-He added water due to the high heat.
-It's an emergency.

2129
01:19:10,645 --> 01:19:12,080
WHAT ABOUT IT?

2130
01:19:12,781 --> 01:19:15,450
It would've been even better
with less water.

2131
01:19:15,517 --> 01:19:17,285
-A bit saltier?
-You were worried for nothing.

2132
01:19:17,352 --> 01:19:19,087
-I shouldn't have done it.
-Is it too bland?

2133
01:19:19,154 --> 01:19:22,257
It's a clear soup
with a strong scent of cilantro,

2134
01:19:22,324 --> 01:19:25,093
so I suddenly want to eat it
with a stronger flavor.

2135
01:19:25,660 --> 01:19:26,895
I WANT TO TRY SOME TOO

2136
01:19:26,962 --> 01:19:28,396
You added lots of cilantro

2137
01:19:28,463 --> 01:19:30,732
-but also kept adding more water.
-The heat was high.

2138
01:19:30,799 --> 01:19:33,335
He thought it would become too salty
because the heat was high.

2139
01:19:33,401 --> 01:19:35,070
Does the cucumber do anything?

2140
01:19:35,137 --> 01:19:36,505
I'm not sure about that.

2141
01:19:36,571 --> 01:19:37,506
DOESN'T DO MUCH

2142
01:19:37,572 --> 01:19:39,608
It wouldn't have tasted good
if the cucumber stood out.

2143
01:19:39,674 --> 01:19:42,043
After all, everything here is green.

2144
01:19:42,110 --> 01:19:44,579
<i>You can't taste the cucumber</i>
<i>behind that much cilantro.</i>

2145
01:19:44,646 --> 01:19:46,982
-It's algae bloom soup.
-Shrek soup.

2146
01:19:47,048 --> 01:19:49,484
I've never had soup this green before.

2147
01:19:50,886 --> 01:19:52,621
Would you like to try the soup?

2148
01:19:53,488 --> 01:19:55,490
Well… I…

2149
01:19:55,557 --> 01:19:57,225
-I can feel it.
-You can feel it?

2150
01:19:57,292 --> 01:19:58,760
He's not really into it.

2151
01:19:58,827 --> 01:20:02,898
He explained it in such detail.

2152
01:20:03,465 --> 01:20:05,066
-You should try it.
-Why don't you try it?

2153
01:20:05,133 --> 01:20:07,469
-The cilantro soup.
-He must love cilantro a lot.

2154
01:20:07,536 --> 01:20:08,603
You like it a lot.

2155
01:20:08,670 --> 01:20:10,739
It's called cilantro algae bloom soup.

2156
01:20:10,806 --> 01:20:12,174
It does seem delicious.

2157
01:20:12,240 --> 01:20:14,276
-Please try it, Soo.
-Cilantro algae bloom soup.

2158
01:20:14,342 --> 01:20:16,878
First, Hangover, Are You Bogging Off?

2159
01:20:19,781 --> 01:20:21,783
-He added starch, right?
-Yes.

2160
01:20:21,850 --> 01:20:23,251
What do you think?

2161
01:20:23,318 --> 01:20:25,620
Mmm. Yes.

2162
01:20:25,687 --> 01:20:26,855
It's good.

2163
01:20:28,390 --> 01:20:30,091
-He must like the flavor.
-Yes.

2164
01:20:30,158 --> 01:20:32,694
It makes you sweat like a pig
when you eat that in the morning.

2165
01:20:32,761 --> 01:20:35,730
-Which one? This?
-That Jeju-style soup.

2166
01:20:35,797 --> 01:20:39,401
It makes you sober up completely
if you eat that and sweat it out.

2167
01:20:40,202 --> 01:20:41,403
-I'm serious.
-He's right.

2168
01:20:41,469 --> 01:20:43,705
All I had was one bite,

2169
01:20:43,772 --> 01:20:45,674
yet I'm about to sweat. It's a wonder.

2170
01:20:45,740 --> 01:20:47,709
Something must hit you with the heat.

2171
01:20:47,776 --> 01:20:51,246
-You feel the alcohol leaving your system.
-It's a wonder.

2172
01:20:51,313 --> 01:20:52,314
PERFECT FOR HANGOVERS

2173
01:20:52,380 --> 01:20:56,084
Those who love bracken
would also love this soup.

2174
01:20:57,352 --> 01:20:59,487
Next, the algae bloom soup.

2175
01:20:59,554 --> 01:21:02,090
-Algae bloom…
-Wait, Poong.

2176
01:21:02,157 --> 01:21:04,326
Have you tried it after making it?

2177
01:21:04,392 --> 01:21:05,861
No, I haven't.

2178
01:21:06,661 --> 01:21:08,730
I think there is a dish like this.

2179
01:21:08,797 --> 01:21:12,834
Somewhere in Southeast Asia,
I believe there is a dish like this.

2180
01:21:12,901 --> 01:21:16,004
I'm sure it exists somewhere.
The world is a big place.

2181
01:21:16,071 --> 01:21:17,939
I think I've seen it before.

2182
01:21:18,006 --> 01:21:21,409
Go Soo now eats <i>gosu</i> soup,
made with lots of <i>gosu</i>.

2183
01:21:22,344 --> 01:21:24,579
Go Soo eats <i>gosu</i>.

2184
01:21:24,646 --> 01:21:25,814
WHAT'S THE CILANTRO POND SOUP LIKE?

2185
01:21:27,015 --> 01:21:29,985
-Go, go!
-Make it into a clip. Go Soo and <i>gosu</i>.

2186
01:21:30,552 --> 01:21:32,487
You're making us quite curious.

2187
01:21:32,554 --> 01:21:33,455
DO YOU NEED ANOTHER 500 WON?

2188
01:21:36,091 --> 01:21:37,359
IS IT GOOD?

2189
01:21:37,425 --> 01:21:40,862
-Do you like it?
-First of all, it's kind of bland,

2190
01:21:40,929 --> 01:21:44,432
-but I can taste the fish fat.
-The tilefish.

2191
01:21:44,499 --> 01:21:46,534
It does taste like tilefish.

2192
01:21:46,601 --> 01:21:48,136
-It tastes like tilefish?
-Yes.

2193
01:21:48,203 --> 01:21:50,972
And what's on my mind now is this.

2194
01:21:51,039 --> 01:21:54,943
-At first, it didn't taste strong.
-I see.

2195
01:21:55,010 --> 01:21:57,445
But after some time,

2196
01:21:57,512 --> 01:21:59,648
I could feel the light flavor coming up.

2197
01:21:59,714 --> 01:22:01,349
Here's my next thought.

2198
01:22:01,416 --> 01:22:02,984
Is it because he didn't use MSG?

2199
01:22:03,051 --> 01:22:04,519
Is that the reason?

2200
01:22:04,586 --> 01:22:07,088
There's a certain clean flavor.

2201
01:22:07,155 --> 01:22:08,957
Please try it, Chef Jong-won.

2202
01:22:09,024 --> 01:22:12,560
That's Poong's algae bloom soup.

2203
01:22:13,261 --> 01:22:15,630
I can taste the tilefish.

2204
01:22:15,697 --> 01:22:18,900
I feel like I'm in Jeju,
and I take a dive into the water.

2205
01:22:18,967 --> 01:22:21,636
But once I jump in,
I find myself in Southeast Asian seas.

2206
01:22:21,703 --> 01:22:22,938
Yes, that's it.

2207
01:22:23,004 --> 01:22:25,507
-How deep did you dive?
-That's how it feels.

2208
01:22:26,641 --> 01:22:28,777
It's now time to choose.

2209
01:22:28,843 --> 01:22:30,345
<i>Press one to pick Jung Ho-young,</i>

2210
01:22:31,112 --> 01:22:32,614
<i>and two for Kim Poong.</i>

2211
01:22:33,915 --> 01:22:36,785
Jong-hyuk had already pushed a button.

2212
01:22:36,851 --> 01:22:39,087
Which one of them is the winner?

2213
01:22:39,154 --> 01:22:40,922
Let's find out. Show us!

2214
01:22:41,623 --> 01:22:44,259
Hangover, Where Are You Going?

2215
01:22:44,326 --> 01:22:46,795
Will it be Poong's algae bloom soup?

2216
01:22:46,861 --> 01:22:50,665
Or will it be
Ho-young's bracken hangover soup?

2217
01:22:50,732 --> 01:22:54,002
Which dish sobered him up
and made him crave more drinks at once?

2218
01:22:54,069 --> 01:22:55,704
Was it Poong's dish

2219
01:22:55,770 --> 01:22:57,205
or Ho-young's dish?

2220
01:22:57,272 --> 01:22:59,007
Who's the winner?

2221
01:23:00,041 --> 01:23:02,243
KIM POONG WINS

2222
01:23:02,610 --> 01:23:04,846
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
FOLLOW ME TO TILEFISH WINS

2223
01:23:04,913 --> 01:23:06,047
Kim Poong wins!

2224
01:23:06,114 --> 01:23:08,083
VICTORY DESPITE LOOKING LIKE ALGAE BLOOM

2225
01:23:08,149 --> 01:23:09,985
Wow, the algae bloom soup wins!

2226
01:23:10,051 --> 01:23:11,619
This sounds like trouble.

2227
01:23:11,686 --> 01:23:13,955
-He won against Ho-young.
-He's insane.

2228
01:23:14,022 --> 01:23:14,889
POONG IS ON A STREAK

2229
01:23:14,956 --> 01:23:16,391
Did Poong deserve it?

2230
01:23:16,458 --> 01:23:20,028
I personally liked how novel it was.

2231
01:23:20,095 --> 01:23:21,162
TOP POINTS FOR BEING ORIGINAL

2232
01:23:21,229 --> 01:23:24,199
As I watched Ho-young cook,
I knew it would turn out delicious.

2233
01:23:25,033 --> 01:23:27,802
But this one I was iffy on,
but once I had a taste,

2234
01:23:27,869 --> 01:23:32,741
it was delicious, and the chili oil
also brought out its flavor.

2235
01:23:32,807 --> 01:23:34,376
I was a bit shocked.

2236
01:23:34,442 --> 01:23:38,279
Before he tried it,
he didn't even know if it was edible.

2237
01:23:38,947 --> 01:23:40,548
You're a water strider
on top of the algae bloom.

2238
01:23:40,615 --> 01:23:43,618
This means Poong has now risen up

2239
01:23:43,685 --> 01:23:46,821
as Son Jong-won's rival.

2240
01:23:46,888 --> 01:23:49,224
Please put a star on Poong!

2241
01:23:49,290 --> 01:23:50,358
KIM POONG, 2ND PLACE WITH 6 STARS!

2242
01:23:50,425 --> 01:23:51,960
-Great game.
-Congratulations!

2243
01:23:52,027 --> 01:23:53,695
Congratulations on your sixth star!

2244
01:23:53,762 --> 01:23:55,964
COMING UP: PREVIEW FOR KO WOO-RIM
AND KANGNAM'S EPISODE

2245
01:23:56,031 --> 01:23:57,899
You're amazing, Poong.

2246
01:23:58,666 --> 01:24:00,402
The men who live with the queens!

2247
01:24:00,468 --> 01:24:02,203
Please welcome Ko Woo-rim and Kangnam!

2248
01:24:02,270 --> 01:24:05,373
The man with a deep, resonant voice
who captured Kim Yuna's heart.

2249
01:24:05,440 --> 01:24:07,409
I think we're mostly calm.

2250
01:24:07,475 --> 01:24:09,010
Honey, what would you like to eat today?

2251
01:24:09,444 --> 01:24:10,545
HOW SWEET OF HIM

2252
01:24:10,612 --> 01:24:12,680
My Sang-hwa is wild.

2253
01:24:12,747 --> 01:24:14,849
If I make the tiniest sound
while she's taking a nap,

2254
01:24:14,916 --> 01:24:16,251
she says, "Kangnam, be quiet!"

2255
01:24:16,484 --> 01:24:17,352
THAT'S THE REALITY

2256
01:24:17,419 --> 01:24:18,486
Just wait eight years.

2257
01:24:18,553 --> 01:24:19,587
DID YOU JUST LAUGH?

2258
01:24:19,654 --> 01:24:21,589
We present his fridge!

2259
01:24:21,656 --> 01:24:23,191
<i>-Ramyeon</i>. He has everything.
-He does.

2260
01:24:23,258 --> 01:24:24,826
I really love to eat,

2261
01:24:24,893 --> 01:24:26,528
so I say I have a PhD in eating.

2262
01:24:26,594 --> 01:24:27,796
Does Yuna call you a doctor?

2263
01:24:27,862 --> 01:24:29,731
She goes,
"Doctor, what are we ordering today?"

2264
01:24:29,998 --> 01:24:30,932
HOW CUTE

2265
01:24:30,999 --> 01:24:33,268
She never knew the concept
of a late-night snack,

2266
01:24:33,334 --> 01:24:35,670
so I gave her her first taste.

2267
01:24:35,737 --> 01:24:36,805
After she tried it,

2268
01:24:36,871 --> 01:24:38,807
she said,
"So this is why people eat late."

2269
01:24:39,107 --> 01:24:40,175
QUEEN-APPROVED DOCTOR

2270
01:24:40,341 --> 01:24:41,810
THE CHEFS BEGIN A COOKING GRAND PRIX

2271
01:24:41,876 --> 01:24:43,244
Nam-no seems aggressive today.

2272
01:24:43,311 --> 01:24:45,580
-Isn't that a genius dish?
-He's a genius.

2273
01:24:45,647 --> 01:24:46,548
That's so pretty.

2274
01:24:46,614 --> 01:24:47,782
-How pretty!
-It's so pretty.

2275
01:24:47,849 --> 01:24:49,284
He's something.

2276
01:24:49,350 --> 01:24:50,185
A WORLD-CLASS PERFORMANCE

2277
01:24:50,485 --> 01:24:51,486
MOVED

2278
01:24:51,986 --> 01:24:53,488
FACING DANGER

2279
01:24:53,855 --> 01:24:55,623
THE DOCTOR OF EATING IS IN SHOCK

2280
01:24:56,024 --> 01:24:58,393
HOW WILL THIS GRAND PRIX END?

2281
01:24:58,460 --> 01:24:59,761
-It's an emergency.
-It's over.

2282
01:24:59,828 --> 01:25:00,762
<i>It's an emergency.</i>

2283
01:25:02,297 --> 01:25:04,499
Even famous chefs make mistakes!

2284
01:25:05,767 --> 01:25:07,502
Even famous chefs!

2285
01:25:17,045 --> 01:25:21,850
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
